OCRPageObject(index=4, markdown="# GR - GENERAL REGULATIONS \n\n## GR. 1 FORMULA SAE COMPETITION OBJECTIVE\n\n## GR.1.1 Collegiate Design Series\n\nSAE International's Collegiate Design Series (CDS) programs prepare undergraduate and graduate engineering students in a variety of disciplines for future employment in mobilityrelated industries by challenging them with a real world, engineering application.\nThrough the Engineering Design Process, experiences may include but are not limited to:\n\n- Project management, budgeting, communication, and resource management skills\n- Team collaboration\n- Applying industry rules and regulations\n- Design, build, and test the performance of a real vehicle\n- Interact and compete with other students from around the globe\n- Develop and prepare technical documentation\n\nStudents also gain valuable exposure to and engagement with industry professionals to enhance 21st century learning skills, to build their own network and help prepare them for the workforce after graduation.\n\n## GR.1.2 Formula SAE Concept\n\nThe Formula SAE ${ }^{\\circledR}$ competitions challenge teams of university undergraduate and graduate students to conceive, design, fabricate, develop and compete with small, formula style vehicles.\n\n## GR.1.3 Engineering Competition\n\nFormula $\\mathrm{SAE}^{\\circledR}$ is an engineering education competition that requires performance demonstration of vehicles in a series of events, both off track and on track against the clock.\n\nEach competition gives teams the chance to demonstrate their creativity and engineering skills in comparison to teams from other universities around the world.\n\n## GR.1.4 Vehicle Design Objectives\n\nGR.1.4.1 Teams are to assume that they work for an engineering firm that is designing, fabricating, testing and demonstrating a prototype vehicle.\n\nGR.1.4.2 The vehicle should have high performance and be sufficiently durable to successfully complete all the events at the Formula SAE competitions.\n\nGR.1.4.3 Additional design factors include: aesthetics, cost, ergonomics, maintainability, and manufacturability.\n\nGR.1.4.4 Each design will be judged and evaluated against other competing designs in a series of Static and Dynamic events to determine the vehicle that best meets the design goals and may be profitably built and marketed.\n\n## GR.1.5 Good Engineering Practices\n\nVehicles entered into Formula SAE competitions should be designed and fabricated in accordance with good engineering practices.", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=5, markdown='# GR. 2 ORGANIZER AUTHORITY \n\n## GR.2.1 General Authority\n\nSAE International and the competition organizing bodies reserve the right to revise the schedule of any competition and/or interpret or modify the competition rules at any time and in any manner that is, in their sole judgment, required for the efficient operation of the event or the Formula SAE series as a whole.\n\n## GR.2.2 Right to Impound\n\nGR.2.2.1 SAE International and other competition organizing bodies may impound any onsite vehicle or part of the vehicle at any time during a competition.\nGR.2.2.2 Team access to the vehicle or impound may be restricted.\n\n## GR.2.3 Problem Resolution\n\nAny problems that arise during the competition will be resolved through the onsite organizers and the decision will be final.\n\n## GR.2.4 Restriction on Vehicle Use\n\nSAE International, competition organizer(s) and officials are not responsible for use of vehicles designed in compliance with these Formula SAE Rules outside of the official Formula SAE competitions.\n\n## GR. 3 TEAM RESPONSIBILITY\n\n## GR.3.1 Rules Compliance\n\nBy registering for a Formula SAE competition, the team, members of the team as individuals, faculty advisors and other personnel of the entering university agree to comply with, and be bound by, these rules and all rule interpretations or procedures issued or announced by SAE International, the Formula SAE Rules Committee and the other organizing bodies.\n\n## GR.3.2 Student Project\n\nBy registering for any university program, the University registered assumes liability of the student project.\n\n## GR.3.3 Understanding the Rules\n\nTeams, team members as individuals and faculty advisors, are responsible for reading and understanding the rules in effect for the competition in which they are participating.\n\n## GR.3.4 Participating in the Competition\n\nGR.3.4.1 Teams, individual team members, faculty advisors and other representatives of a registered university who are present onsite at a competition are "participating in the competition" from the time they arrive at the competition site until they depart the site at the conclusion of the competition or earlier by withdrawing.\nGR.3.4.2 All team members, faculty advisors and other university representatives must cooperate with, and follow all instructions from, competition organizers, officials and judges.\n\n## GR.3.5 Forfeit for Non Appearance\n\nGR.3.5.1 It is the responsibility of each team to be in the right place at the right time.\nGR.3.5.2 If a team is not present and ready to compete at the scheduled time, they forfeit their attempt at that event.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=6, markdown='GR.3.5.3 There are no makeups for missed appearances.\n\n# GR. 4 RULES AUTHORITY AND ISSUE \n\n## GR.4.1 Rules Authority\n\nThe Formula SAE Rules are the responsibility of the Formula SAE Rules Committee and are issued under the authority of the SAE International Collegiate Design Series.\n\n## GR.4.2 Rules Validity\n\nGR.4.2.1 The Formula SAE Rules posted on the website and dated for the calendar year of the competition are the rules in effect for the competition.\nGR.4.2.2 Rules appendices or supplements may be posted on the website and incorporated into the rules by reference.\nGR.4.2.3 Additional guidance or reference documents may be posted on the website.\nGR.4.2.4 Any rules, questions, or resolutions from previous years are not valid for the current competition year.\n\n## GR.4.3 Rules Alterations\n\nGR.4.3.1 The Formula SAE rules may be revised, updated, or amended at any time\nGR.4.3.2 Official designated announcements from the Formula SAE Rules Committee, SAE International or the other organizing bodies are to be considered part of, and have the same validity as, these rules.\n\nGR.4.3.3 Draft rules or proposals may be issued for comments, however they are a courtesy, are not valid for any competitions, and may or may not be implemented in whole or in part.\n\n## GR.4.4 Rules Compliance\n\nGR.4.4.1 All participants must comply with the latest issue of the Formula SAE Rules. Refer to the FSAE Online Website to verify the current version.\nGR.4.4.2 Teams and team members must comply with the general rules and any specific rules for each competition they enter.\nGR.4.4.3 Any regulations pertaining to the use of the competition site by teams or individuals and which are posted, announced and/or otherwise publicly available are incorporated into the Formula SAE Rules by reference.\n\nAs examples, all competition site waiver requirements, speed limits, parking and facility use rules apply to Formula SAE participants.\n\n## GR.4.5 Violations on Intent\n\nThe violation of the intent of a rule will be considered a violation of the rule itself.\n\n## GR. 5 RULES OF CONDUCT\n\n## GR.5.1 Unsportsmanlike Conduct\n\nIf unsportsmanlike conduct occurs, the team will receive a warning from an official.\nA second violation will result in expulsion of the team from the competition.\n\n## GR.5.2 Official Instructions\n\nFailure of a team member to follow an instruction or command directed specifically to that team or team member will result in a 25 point penalty.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=7, markdown='# GR.5.3 Arguments with Officials \n\nArgument with, or disobedience of, any official may result in the team being eliminated from the competition.\n\nAll members of the team may be immediately escorted from the grounds.\n\n## GR.5.4 Alcohol and Illegal Material\n\nGR.5.4.1 Alcohol, illegal drugs, weapons or other illegal material are prohibited on the competition site during the entire competition.\nGR.5.4.2 Any violation of this rule by any team member or faculty advisor will cause immediate disqualification and expulsion of the entire team.\nGR.5.4.3 Any use of drugs, or the use of alcohol by an underage individual will be reported to the local authorities.\n\n## GR.5.5 Smoking - Prohibited\n\nSmoking and e-cigarette use is prohibited in all competition areas.\n\n## GR. 6 RULES FORMAT AND USE\n\n## GR.6.1 Definition of Terms\n\n- Must - designates a requirement\n- Must NOT - designates a prohibition or restriction\n- Should - gives an expectation\n- May - gives permission, not a requirement and not a recommendation\n\n\n## GR.6.2 Capitalized Terms\n\nItems or areas which have specific definitions or are covered by specific rules are capitalized.\nFor example, "Rules Questions" or "Primary Structure"\n\n## GR.6.3 Headings\n\nThe article, section and paragraph headings in these rules are provided only to facilitate reading: they do not affect the paragraph contents.\n\n## GR.6.4 Applicability\n\nGR.6.4.1 Unless otherwise specified, all rules apply to all vehicles at all times\nGR.6.4.2 Rules specific to vehicles based on their powertrain will be specified as such in the rule text:\n\n- Internal Combustion "IC" or "IC Only"\n- Electric Vehicle "EV" or "EV Only"\n\n\n## GR.6.5 Figures and Illustrations\n\nFigures and illustrations give clarification or guidance, but are rules only when referred to in the text of a rule\n\n## GR.6.6 Change Identification\n\nAny summary of changed rules and/or changed portions marked in the rules themselves are provided for courtesy, and may or may not include all changes.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=8, markdown='# GR. 7 RULES QUESTIONS \n\n## GR.7.1 Question Types\n\nDesignated officials will answer questions that are not already answered in the rules or FAQs or that require new or novel rule interpretations.\nRules Questions may also be used to request approval, as specified in these rules.\n\n## GR.7.2 Question Format\n\nGR.7.2.1 All Rules Questions must include:\n\n- Full name and contact information of the person submitting the question\n- University name - no abbreviations\n- The specific competition your team has, or is planning to, enter.\n- Number of the applicable rule(s)\n\nGR.7.2.2 Response Time\n\n- $\\quad$ Please allow a minimum of two weeks for a response\n- Do not resubmit questions\n\nGR.7.2.3 Submission Addresses\na. Teams entering Formula SAE competitions: Follow the link and instructions published on the FSAE Online Website to "Submit a Rules Question"\nb. Teams entering other competitions please visit those respective competition websites for further instructions.\n\n## GR.7.3 Question Publication\n\nAny submitted question and the official answer may be reproduced and freely distributed, in both complete and edited versions.\n\n## GR. 8 PROTESTS\n\n## GR.8.1 Cause for Protest\n\nA team may protest any rule interpretation, score or official action (unless specifically excluded from Protest) which they feel has caused some actual, non trivial, harm to their team, or has had a substantive effect on their score.\n\n## GR.8.2 Preliminary Review - Required\n\nQuestions about scoring, judging, policies or any official action must be brought to the attention of the organizer or SAE International staff for an informal preliminary review before a protest may be filed.\n\n## GR.8.3 Protest Format\n\n- All protests must be filed in writing\n- The completed protest must be presented to the organizer or SAE International staff by the team captain.\n- Team video or data acquisition will not be reviewed as part of a protest.\n\n\n## GR.8.4 Protest Point Bond\n\nA team must post a 25 point protest bond which will be forfeited if their protest is rejected.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=9, markdown='# GR.8.5 Protest Period \n\nProtests concerning any aspect of the competition must be filed in the protest period announced by the competition organizers or 30 minutes of the posting of the scores of the event to which the protest relates.\n\n## GR.8.6 Decision\n\nThe decision regarding any protest is final.\n\n## GR. 9 VEHICLE ELIGIBILITY\n\n## GR.9.1 Student Developed Vehicle\n\nGR.9.1.1 Vehicles entered into Formula SAE competitions must be conceived, designed, fabricated and maintained by the student team members without direct involvement from professional engineers, automotive engineers, racers, machinists or related professionals.\nGR.9.1.2 Information Sources\nThe student team may use any literature or knowledge related to design and information from professionals or from academics as long as the information is given as a discussion of alternatives with their pros and cons.\nGR.9.1.3 Professional Assistance\nProfessionals must not make design decisions or drawings. The Faculty Advisor may be required to sign a statement of compliance with this restriction.\nGR.9.1.4 Student Fabrication\nStudents should perform all fabrication tasks\n\n## GR.9.2 Definitions\n\n## GR.9.2.1 Competition Year\n\nThe period beginning at the event of the Formula SAE series where the vehicle first competes and continuing until the start of the corresponding event held approximately 12 months later.\n\n## GR.9.2.2 First Year Vehicle\n\nA vehicle which has, at minimum, a newly built chassis and is in its initial Competition Year\n\n## GR.9.2.3 Second Year Vehicle\n\nA vehicle which has competed in a previous Competition Year\n\n## GR.9.2.4 Third Year Vehicle\n\nA vehicle which has competed in more than one previous Competition Year\n\n## GR.9.3 Formula SAE Competition Eligibility\n\nGR.9.3.1 Only First Year Vehicles may enter the Formula SAE Competitions.\na. If there is any question about the status as a First Year Vehicle, the team must provide additional information and/or evidence.\nGR.9.3.2 Second Year Vehicles must not enter Formula SAE Competitions, unless permitted by the organizer of the specific competition.\nGR.9.3.3 Third Year Vehicles must not enter any Formula SAE Competitions', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=10, markdown='# AD - ADMINISTRATIVE REGULATIONS \n\n## AD. 1 THE FORMULA SAE SERIES\n\n## AD.1.1 Rule Variations\n\nAll competitions in the Formula SAE Series may post rule variations specific to the operation of the events in their countries. Vehicle design requirements and restrictions will remain unchanged. Any rule variations will be posted on the websites specific to those competitions.\n\n## AD.1.2 Official Announcements and Competition Information\n\nTeams must read the published announcements by SAE International and the other organizing bodies and be familiar with all official announcements concerning the competitions and any released rules interpretations.\n\n## AD.1.3 Official Languages\n\nThe official language of the Formula SAE series is English.\nDocument submissions, presentations and discussions in English are acceptable at all competitions in the series.\n\n## AD. 2 OFFICIAL INFORMATION SOURCES\n\nThe following websites are referenced in these rules. Refer to the websites for additional information and resources.\n\n## AD.2.1 Event Website\n\nThe Event Website for Formula SAE is specific to each competition, refer to:\nhttps://www.sae.org/attend/student-events\n\n## AD.2.2 FSAE Online Website\n\nThe FSAE Online website is at: http://fsaeonline.com/\nAD.2.2.1 Documents, forms, and information are accessed from the "Series Resources" link\nAD.2.2.2 Each registered team must have an account on the FSAE Online Website.\nAD.2.2.3 Each team must have one or more persons as Team Captain. The Team Captain must accept Team Members.\n\nAD.2.2.4 Only persons designated Team Members or Team Captains are able to upload documents to the website.\n\n## AD.2.3 Contacts\n\nContact collegiatecompetitions@sae.org with any problems/comments/concerns\nConsult the specific website for the other competitions requirements.\n\n## AD. 3 INDIVIDUAL PARTICIPATION REQUIREMENTS\n\n## AD.3.1 Eligibility\n\nAD.3.1.1 Team members must be enrolled as degree seeking undergraduate or graduate students in the college or university of the team with which they are participating.\nAD.3.1.2 Team members who have graduated during the seven month period prior to the competition remain eligible to participate.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=11, markdown="AD.3.1.3 Teams which are formed with members from two or more universities are treated as a single team. A student at any university making up the team may compete at any competition where the team participates. The multiple universities are treated as one university with the same eligibility requirements.\nAD.3.1.4 Each team member may participate at a competition for only one team. This includes competitions where the University enters both IC and EV teams.\n\n# AD.3.2 Age \n\nTeam members must be minimum 18 years of age.\n\n## AD.3.3 Driver's License\n\nTeam members who will drive a competition vehicle at any time during a competition must hold a valid, government issued driver's license.\n\n## AD.3.4 Society Membership\n\nTeam members must be members of SAE International\nProof of membership, such as membership card, is required at the competition.\n\n## AD.3.5 Medical Insurance\n\nIndividual medical insurance coverage is required and is the sole responsibility of the participant.\n\n## AD.3.6 Disabled Accessibility\n\nTeam members who require accessibility for areas outside of ADA Compliance must contact organizers at collegiatecompetitions@sae.org prior to start of competition.\n\n## AD. 4 INDIVIDUAL REGISTRATION REQUIREMENTS\n\n## AD.4.1 Preliminary Registration\n\nAD.4.1.1 All students and faculty must be affiliated to your respective school /college/university on the Event Website before the deadline shown on the Event Website\nAD.4.1.2 International student participants (or unaffiliated Faculty Advisors) who are not SAE International members must create a free customer account profile on www.sae.org. Upon completion, please email collegiatecompetitions@sae.org the assigned customer number stating also the event and university affiliation.\n\n## AD.4.2 Onsite Registration\n\nAD.4.2.1 All team members and faculty advisors must register at the competition site\nAD.4.2.2 All onsite participants, including students, faculty and volunteers, must sign a liability waiver upon registering onsite.\nAD.4.2.3 Onsite registration must be completed before the vehicle may be unloaded, uncrated or worked upon in any manner.\n\n## AD. 5 TEAM ADVISORS AND OFFICERS\n\n## AD.5.1 Faculty Advisor\n\nAD.5.1.1 Each team must have a Faculty Advisor appointed by their university.\nAD.5.1.2 The Faculty Advisor should accompany the team to the competition and will be considered by the officials to be the official university representative.", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=12, markdown='AD.5.1.3 Faculty Advisors:\na. May advise their teams on general engineering and engineering project management theory\nb. Must not design, build or repair any part of the vehicle\nc. Must not develop any documentation or presentation\n\n# AD.5.2 Electrical System Officer (EV Only) \n\nThe Electrical System Officer (ESO) is responsible for all electrical operations of the vehicle during the event\n\nAD.5.2.1 Every participating team must appoint one or more ESO for the event\nAD.5.2.2 The ESO must meet the following:\na. Is a valid team member, see AD. 3 Individual Participation Requirements\nb. One or more ESO must not be a driver.\nc. Is certified or has received appropriate practical training whether formal or informal for working with High Voltage systems in automotive vehicles.\n\nGive details of the training on the ESO/ESA form\nAD.5.2.3 Duties of the ESO - see EV.11.1.1\n\n## AD.5.3 Electric System Advisor (EV Only)\n\nAD.5.3.1 The Electrical System Advisor (ESA) must be a professionally competent person(s) nominated by the team who can advise on the electrical and control systems that will be integrated into the vehicle. The faculty advisor may also be the ESA if all the requirements below are met.\n\nAD.5.3.2 The ESA must supply details of their experience of electrical and/or control systems engineering as used in the vehicle on the ESO/ESA form for approval by the organizers.\n\nAD.5.3.3 The ESA must be sufficiently qualified to advise the team on their proposed electrical and control system designs based on significant experience of the technology being developed and its implementation into vehicles or other safety critical systems. More than one person may be needed.\n\nAD.5.3.4 The ESA must advise the team on the merits of any relevant engineering solutions. Solutions should be discussed, questioned and approved before they are implemented into the final vehicle design.\n\nAD.5.3.5 The ESA should advise the students on any required training to work with the systems on the vehicle.\n\nAD.5.3.6 The ESA must review the Electrical System Form and to confirm that in principle the vehicle has been designed using good engineering practices.\n\nAD.5.3.7 The ESA must ensure that the team communicates any unusual aspects of the design to the organizers to reduce the risk of exclusion or significant changes being required to pass Technical Inspection.\n\n## AD. 6 COMPETITION REGISTRATION\n\n## AD.6.1 General Information\n\nAD.6.1.1 Registration for Formula SAE competitions must be completed on the Event Website.\nAD.6.1.2 Refer to the individual competition websites for registration requirements for other competitions', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=13, markdown="# AD.6.2 Registration Details \n\nAD.6.2.1 Refer to the Event Website for specific registration requirements and details.\n\n- Registration limits and Waitlist limits will be posted on the Event Website.\n- Registration will open at the date and time posted on the Event Website.\n- Registration(s) may have limitations\n\nAD.6.2.2 Once a competition reaches the registration limit, a Waitlist will open.\nAD.6.2.3 Beginning on the date and time posted on the Event Website, any remaining slots will be available to any team on a first come, first serve basis.\nAD.6.2.4 Registration and the Waitlist will close at the date and time posted on the Event Website or when all available slots have been taken, whichever occurs first.\n\n## AD.6.3 Registration Fees\n\nAD.6.3.1 Registration fees must be paid to the organizer by the deadline specified on the respective competition website.\n\nAD.6.3.2 Registration fees are not refundable and not transferrable to any other competition.\n\n## AD.6.4 Waitlist\n\nAD.6.4.1 Waitlisted teams must submit all documents by the same deadlines as registered teams to remain on the Waitlist.\n\nAD.6.4.2 Once a team withdraws from the competition, the organizer will inform the next team on the Waitlist by email (the individual who registered the team to the Waitlist) that a spot on the registered list has opened.\n\nAD.6.4.3 The team will then have 24 hours to accept or reject the position and an additional 24 hours to have the registration payment completed or in process.\n\n## AD.6.5 Withdrawals\n\nRegistered teams that will not attend the competition must inform the organizer, as posted on the Event Website.\n\n## AD. 7 COMPETITION SITE\n\n## AD.7.1 Personal Vehicles\n\nPersonal cars and trailers must be parked in designated areas only. Only authorized vehicles will be allowed in the track areas.\n\n## AD.7.2 Motorcycles, Bicycles, Rollerblades, etc. - Prohibited\n\nThe use of motorcycles, quads, bicycles, scooters, skateboards, rollerblades or similar personcarrying devices by team members and spectators in any part of the competition area, including the paddocks, is prohibited.\n\n## AD.7.3 Self-propelled Pit Carts, Tool Boxes, etc. - Prohibited\n\nThe use of self-propelled pit carts, tool boxes, tire carriers or similar motorized devices in any part of the competition site, including the paddocks, is prohibited.\n\n## AD.7.4 Trash Cleanup\n\nAD.7.4.1 Cleanup of trash and debris is the responsibility of the teams.\n\n- The team's work area should be kept uncluttered", images=[], DOCUMENT REQUIREMENTS \n\n## DR. 1 DOCUMENTATION\n\n## DR.1.1 Requirements\n\nDR.1.1.1 The documents supporting each vehicle must be submitted before the deadlines posted on the Event Website or otherwise published by the organizer.\n\nDR.1.1.2 The procedures for submitting documents are published on the Event Website or otherwise identified by the organizer.\n\n## DR.1.2 Definitions\n\nDR.1.2.1 Submission Date\nThe date and time of upload to the website\nDR.1.2.2 Submission Deadline\nThe date and time by which the document must be uploaded or submitted\nDR.1.2.3 No Submissions Accepted After\nThe last date and time that documents may be uploaded or submitted\nDR.1.2.4 Late Submission\n\n- Uploaded after the Submission Deadline and prior to No Submissions Accepted After\n- Submitted largely incomplete prior to or after the Submission Deadline\n\nDR.1.2.5 Not Submitted\n\n- Not uploaded prior to No Submissions Accepted After\n- Not in the specified form or format\n\nDR.1.2.6 Amount Late\nThe number of days between the Submission Deadline and the Submission Date.\nAny partial day is rounded up to a full day.\nExamples: submitting a few minutes late would be one day penalty; submitting 25 hours late would be two days penalty\n\nDR.1.2.7 Reviewer\nA designated event official who is assigned to review and accept a Submission\n\n## DR. 2 SUBMISSION VEHICLE REQUIREMENTS \n\n## V. 1 CONFIGURATION\n\nThe vehicle must be open wheeled and open cockpit (a formula style body) with four wheels that are not in a straight line.\n\n## V.1.1 Open Wheel\n\nOpen Wheel vehicles must satisfy all of the following criteria:\na. The top $180^{\\circ}$ of the wheels/tires must be unobstructed when viewed from vertically above the wheel.\nb. The wheels/tires must be unobstructed when viewed from the side.\nc. No part of the vehicle may enter a keep out zone defined by two lines extending vertically from positions 75 mm in front of and 75 mm aft of, the outer diameter of the front and rear tires in the side view elevation of the vehicle, with tires steered straight ahead. This keep out zone will extend laterally from the outside plane of the wheel/tire to the inboard plane of the wheel/tire.\n![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)\n\n## V.1.2 Wheelbase\n\nThe vehicle must have a minimum wheelbase of 1525 mm\n\n## V.1.3 Vehicle Track\n\nV.1.3.1 The track and center of gravity must combine to provide sufficient rollover stability. See IN.9.2\nV.1.3.2 The smaller track of the vehicle (front or rear) must be no less than $75 \\%$ of the larger track.', images=[OCRImageObject(id='img-0.jpeg', top_left_x=306, top_left_y=851, bottom_right_x=1371, bottom_right_y=1584, image_base64='data:image/jpeg;base64,', image_annotation='{\n  "image_type": "Technical Drawing",\n  "short_description": "A technical drawing showing restricted and unrestricted areas around circular components.",\n  "summary": "This technical drawing illustrates specific spatial constraints around two circular components. Each circular component has a diameter of 75 mm, and the restricted areas are clearly defined around these components. The drawing also includes a legend explaining the patterns used to denote the restricted and unrestricted areas."\n}')], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=19, markdown="# V.1.4 Ground Clearance \n\nV.1.4.1 Ground clearance must be sufficient to prevent any portion of the vehicle except the tires from touching the ground during dynamic events\nV.1.4.2 The distance to the ground below the Lower Side Impact Structure ( F.6.4.5, F.7.5.1 ) at its lowest point should be 75 mm or less\nV.1.4.3 Intentional or excessive ground contact of any portion of the vehicle other than the tires will forfeit a run or an entire dynamic event\n\nThe intent is that sliding skirts or other devices that by design, fabrication or as a consequence of moving, contact the track surface are prohibited and any unintended contact with the ground which causes damage, or in the opinion of the Dynamic Event Officials could result in damage to the track, will result in forfeit of a run or an entire dynamic event\n\n## V. 2 DRIVER\n\n## V.2.1 Accommodation\n\nV.2.1.1 The vehicle must be able to accommodate drivers of sizes ranging from 5th percentile female up to 95th percentile male.\n\n- Accommodation includes driver position, driver controls, and driver equipment.\n- Anthropometric data may be found on the FSAE Online Website.\nV.2.1.2 The driver's head and hands must not contact the ground in any rollover attitude.\n\n\n## V.2.2 Visibility\n\na. The driver must have sufficient visibility to the front and sides of the vehicle\nb. When seated in a normal driving position, the driver must have a minimum field of vision of $100^{\\circ}$ to both sides\nc. If mirrors are required for this rule, they must remain in place and adjusted to enable the required visibility throughout all dynamic events.\n\n## V. 3 SUSPENSION AND STEERING\n\n## V.3.1 Suspension\n\nV.3.1.1 The vehicle must have a fully operational suspension system with shock absorbers, front and rear, with usable minimum wheel travel of 50 mm , with a driver seated.\nV.3.1.2 Officials may disqualify vehicles which do not represent a serious attempt at an operational suspension system, or which demonstrate handling inappropriate for an autocross circuit.\nV.3.1.3 All suspension mounting points must be visible at Technical Inspection by direct view or by removing any covers.\nV.3.1.4 Fasteners in the Suspension system are Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2\nV.3.1.5 All spherical rod ends and spherical bearings on the suspension and steering must be one of:\n\n- Mounted in double shear\n- Captured by having a screw/bolt head or washer with an outside diameter that is larger than spherical bearing housing inside diameter.\n\n\n## V.3.2 Steering\n\nV.3.2.1 The Steering Wheel must be mechanically connected to the front wheels", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=20, markdown='V.3.2.2 Electrically actuated steering of the front wheels is prohibited\nV.3.2.3 Steering systems must use a rigid mechanical linkage capable of tension and compression loads for operation\nV.3.2.4 The steering system must have positive steering stops that prevent the steering linkages from locking up (the inversion of a four bar linkage at one of the pivots). The stops:\na. Must prevent the wheels and tires from contacting suspension, bodywork, or Chassis during the track events\nb. May be placed on the uprights or on the rack\nV.3.2.5 Allowable steering system free play is limited to seven degrees (7) total measured at the steering wheel.\nV.3.2.6 The steering rack must be mechanically attached to the Chassis F.5.14\nV.3.2.7 Joints between all components attaching the Steering Wheel to the steering rack must be mechanical and be visible at Technical Inspection. Bonded joints without a mechanical backup are not permitted.\nV.3.2.8 Fasteners in the steering system are Critical Fasteners, see T.8.2\nV.3.2.9 Spherical rod ends and spherical bearings in the steering must meet V.3.1.5 above\nV.3.2.10 Rear wheel steering may be used.\na. Rear wheel steering must incorporate mechanical stops to limit the range of angular movement of the rear wheels to a maximum of six degrees ( $6^{\\circ}$ ).\nb. The team must provide the ability for the steering angle range to be verified at Technical Inspection with a driver in the vehicle.\nc. Rear wheel steering may be electrically actuated.\n\n# V.3.3 Steering Wheel \n\nV.3.3.1 In any angular position, the Steering Wheel must meet T.1.4.4\nV.3.3.2 The Steering Wheel must be attached to the column with a quick disconnect.\nV.3.3.3 The driver must be able to operate the quick disconnect while in the normal driving position with gloves on.\nV.3.3.4 The Steering Wheel must have a continuous perimeter that is near circular or near oval. The outer perimeter profile may have some straight sections, but no concave sections. "H", "Figure 8", or cutout wheels are not allowed.\n\n## V. 4 WHEELS AND TIRES\n\n## V.4.1 Wheel Size\n\nWheels must be 203.2 mm ( 8.0 inches) or more in diameter.\n\n## V.4.2 Wheel Attachment\n\nV.4.2.1 Any wheel mounting system that uses a single retaining nut must incorporate a device to retain the nut and the wheel if the nut loosens.\n\nA second nut (jam nut) does not meet this requirement\nV.4.2.2 Teams using modified lug bolts or custom designs must provide proof that Good Engineering Practices have been followed in their design.\nV.4.2.3 If used, aluminum wheel nuts must be hard anodized and in pristine condition.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=21, markdown='# V.4.3 Tires \n\nVehicles may have two types of tires, Dry and Wet\nV.4.3.1 Dry Tires\na. The tires on the vehicle when it is presented for Technical Inspection.\nb. May be any size or type, slicks or treaded.\nV.4.3.2 Wet Tires\n\nAny size or type of treaded or grooved tire where:\n\n- The tread pattern or grooves were molded in by the tire manufacturer, or were cut by the tire manufacturer or appointed agent.\n\nAny grooves that have been cut must have documented proof that this rule was met\n\n- There is a minimum tread depth of 2.4 mm\nV.4.3.3 Tire Set\na. All four Dry Tires and Wheels or all four Wet Tires and Wheels do not have to be identical.\nb. Once each tire set has been presented for Technical Inspection, any tire compound or size, or wheel type or size must not be changed.\nV.4.3.4 Tire Pressure\na. Tire Pressure must be in the range allowed by the manufacturer at all times.\nb. Tire Pressure may be inspected at any time\nV.4.3.5 Requirements for All Tires\na. Teams must not perform any hand cutting, grooving or modification of the tires.\nb. Tire warmers are not allowed.\nc. No traction enhancers may be applied to the tires at any time onsite at the competition.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=22, markdown="# F - CHASSIS AND STRUCTURAL \n\n## F. 1 DEFINITIONS\n\n## F.1.1 Chassis\n\nThe fabricated structural assembly that supports all functional vehicle systems.\nThis assembly may be a single fabricated structure, multiple fabricated structures or a combination of composite and welded structures.\n\n## F.1.2 Frame Member\n\nA minimum representative single piece of uncut, continuous tubing.\n\n## F.1.3 Monocoque\n\nA type of Chassis where loads are supported by the external panels\n\n## F.1.4 Main Hoop\n\nA roll bar located alongside or immediately aft of the driver's torso.\n\n## F.1.5 Front Hoop\n\nA roll bar located above the driver's legs, in proximity to the steering wheel.\n\n## F.1.6 Roll Hoop(s)\n\nReferring to both the Front Hoop AND the Main Hoop\n\n## F.1.7 Roll Hoop Bracing Supports\n\nThe structure from the lower end of the Roll Hoop Bracing back to the Roll Hoop(s).\n\n## F.1.8 Front Bulkhead\n\nA planar structure that provides protection for the driver's feet.\n\n## F.1.9 Impact Attenuator\n\nA deformable, energy absorbing device located forward of the Front Bulkhead.\n\n## F.1.10 Primary Structure\n\nThe combination of the following components:\n\n- Front Bulkhead and Front Bulkhead Support\n- Front Hoop, Main Hoop, Roll Hoop Braces and Supports\n- Side Impact Structure\n- (EV Only) Tractive System Protection and Rear Impact Protection\n- Any Frame Members, guides, or supports that transfer load from the Driver Restraint System\n\n\n## F.1.11 Primary Structure Envelope\n\nA volume enclosed by multiple tangent planes, each of which follows the exact outline of the Primary Structure Frame Members\n\n## F.1.12 Major Structure\n\nThe portion of the Chassis that lies inside the Primary Structure Envelope, excluding the Main Hoop Bracing and the portion of the Main Hoop above a horizontal plane located at the top of the Upper Side Impact Member or top of the Side Impact Zone.", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=23, markdown='# F.1.13 Rollover Protection Envelope \n\nThe Primary Structure plus a plane from the top of the Main Hoop to the top of the Front Hoop, plus a plane from the top of the Main Hoop to the rearmost Triangulated structural tube, or monocoque equivalent.\n\n* If there are no Triangulated Structural members aft of the Main Hoop, the Rollover Protection Envelope ends at the rear plane of the Main Hoop\n![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)\n\n\n## F.1.14 Tire Surface Envelope\n\nThe volume enclosed by tangent Document the Primary Structure and show compliance with the Formula SAE Rules\nb. Non Welded Properties for continuous material calculations:\n\nYoung\'s Modulus (E) $=200 \\mathrm{GPa}(29,000 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nYield Strength (Sy) $=305 \\mathrm{MPa}(44.2 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nUltimate Strength (Su) $=365 \\mathrm{MPa}(52.9 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nb. Welded Properties for discontinuous material such as joint calculations:\n\nYield Strength (Sy) $=180 \\mathrm{MPa}(26 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nUltimate Strength (Su) $=300 \\mathrm{MPa}(43.5 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nF.3.4.3 Where Welded tubing reinforcements are required (such as inserts for bolt holes or material to support suspension cutouts), Equivalence of the Welded tube and reinforcement must be shown to the original Non Welded tube in the SES\n\n# F.3.5 Alternative Tubing Materials \n\nF.3.5.1 Alternative Materials may be used for applications shown as permitted in F.3.2.1\nF.3.5.2 If any Alternative Materials are used, the SES must contain:\na. Documentation of material type, (purchase receipt, shipping document or letter of donation) and the material properties.\nb. Calculations that show equivalent to or better than the minimum requirements for steel tubing in the application as listed in F.3.4.1 for yield and ultimate strengths matching the Non Welded Steel properties from F.3.4.2.a above in bending, buckling and tension, for buckling modulus and for energy dissipation\nc. Details of the manufacturing technique and process\nF.3.5.3 Aluminum Tubing\na. Minimum Wall Thickness for Aluminum Tubing: Non Welded 2.0 mm\n\nWelded $\\quad 3.0 \\mathrm{~mm}$\nb. Non Welded properties for aluminum alloy 6061-T6 for calculations in an SES must be:\n\nYoung\'s Modulus (E) $\\quad 69 \\mathrm{GPa}(10,000 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nYield Strength (Sy) $\\quad 240 \\mathrm{MPa}(34.8 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nUltimate Strength (Su) $290 \\mathrm{MPa}(42.1 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nc. Welded properties for aluminum alloy 6061-T6 for calculations in an SES must be:\n\nYield Strength (Sy) $\\quad 115 \\mathrm{MPa}(16.7 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nUltimate Strength (Su) $175 \\mathrm{MPa}(25.4 \\mathrm{ksi})$\nd. If welding is used on a regulated aluminum structure, the equivalent yield strength must be considered in the "as welded" condition for the alloy used unless the team provides detailed proof that the frame or component has been properly solution heat treated, artificially aged, and not subject to heating during team manufacturing.\ne. If aluminum was solution heat treated and age hardened to increase its strength after welding, the team must supply evidence as to how the process was performed.\nThis includes, but is not limited to, the heat treating facility used, the process applied, and the fixturing used.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=27, markdown='# F. 4 COMPOSITE AND OTHER MATERIALS \n\n## F.4.1 Requirements\n\nIf any composite or other material is used, the SES must contain:\nF.4.1.1 Documentation of material type, (purchase receipt, shipping document or letter of donation) and the material properties.\nF.4.1.2 Details of the manufacturing technique and/or composite layup technique as well as the structural material used (examples - cloth type, weight, and resin type, number of layers, core material, and skin material if metal).\nF.4.1.3 Calculations that show equivalence of the structure to one of similar geometry made to meet the minimum requirements for a structure made from steel tubing per F.3.2. Equivalency calculations must be submitted for energy dissipation, yield and ultimate strengths in bending, buckling, and tension.\nF.4.1.4 Construction dates of the test panel(s) and monocoque, and approximate age(s) of the materials used.\n\nThe intent is for the test panel to use the same material batch, material age, material storage, and student layup quality as the monocoque.\n\n## F.4.2 Quasi-Isotropic Layup\n\nA layup with equal fiber strength and stiffness along any orientation in the plane of the layup.\na. When a layup has equal fiber properties and mass in the $0 / 90 /+45 /-45$ directions, the layup may be considered Quasi-Isotropic\n\n## F.4.3 Laminate and Material Testing\n\n## F.4.3.1 Testing Requirements\n\na. Any tested samples must be engraved with the construction date, sample name, and peak test force.\nb. The same set of test results must not be used for different monocoques in different years.\n\nThe intent is for the test panel to use the same material batch, material age, material storage, and student layup quality as the monocoque.\n\n## F.4.3.2 Primary Structure Laminate Testing\n\nTeams must build new representative test panels for each ply schedule used in the regulated regions of the new chassis as a flat panel and perform a 3 point bending test on these panels. Refer to F.4.3.4\na. Test panels must:\n\n- Measure one of the two options: $138 \\mathrm{~mm} \\times 500 \\mathrm{~mm}$ OR $275 \\mathrm{~mm} \\times 500 \\mathrm{~mm}$\n- Be supported by a span distance of 400 mm\n- Have equal surface area for the top and bottom skin\n- Have bare edges, without skin material\nb. The SES must include:\n- Data from the 3 point bending tests\n- Pictures of the test samples', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=28, markdown='- A picture of the test sample and test setup showing a measurement documenting the supported span distance used in the SES\nc. Test panel results must be used to derive stiffness, yield strength, ultimate strength and absorbed energy properties by the SES formula and limits for the purpose of calculating laminate panels equivalency corresponding to Primary Structure regions of the chassis.\nd. Test panels must use the thickest core associated with each skin layup.\n\nDesigns may use core thickness that is $50 \\%-100 \\%$ of the test panel core thickness associated with each skin layup.\ne. Calculation of derived properties must use the part of test data where deflection is 50 mm or less\nf. Calculation of absorbed energy must use the integral of force times displacement\nF.4.3.3 Comparison Test\n\nTeams must make an equivalent test that will determine any compliance in the test rig and establish an absorbed energy value of the baseline tubes.\na. The comparison test must use two Side Impact steel tubes (F.3.2.1.e)\nb. The steel tubes must be tested to a minimum displacement of 19.0 mm\nc. The calculation of absorbed energy must use the integral of force times displacement from the initiation of load to a displacement of 19.0 mm\nF.4.3.4 Test Conduct\na. The Laminate test F.4.3.2 and the Comparison test F.4.3.2e must use the same fixture\nb. The load applicator used to test any panel/tubes as required in this section F.4.3 must be:\n\n- Metallic\n- Radius 50 mm\nc. The load applicator must overhang the test piece to prevent edge loading\nd. Any other material must not be placed between the load applicator and the items on test\n![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)\nF.4.3.5 Perimeter Shear Test\na. The Perimeter Shear Test must be completed by measuring the force required to push or pull a 25 mm diameter flat punch through a flat laminate sample.\nb. The sample must:\n- Measure $100 \\mathrm{~mm} \\times 100 \\mathrm{~mm}$ minimum\n- Have core and skin thicknesses identical to those used in the actual application\n- Be manufactured using the same materials and processes', images=[OCRImageObject(id='img-5.jpeg', top_left_x=224, top_left_y=1412, bottom_right_x=1475, bottom_right_y=1645, image_base64='data:image/jpeg;base64,', image_annotation='{\n  "image_type": "Diagram",\n  "short_description": "A diagram showing a test specimen with a load applicator.",\n  "summary": "The image is a diagram illustrating a test setup. Do two separate pull tests with different orientations of the adhesive joint:\n\n- Parallel to the pull direction, with the adhesive joint in pure shear\n- T peel normal to the pull direction, with the adhesive joint in peel\nb. The samples used must:\n- Have skin thicknesses identical to those used in the actual monocoque\n- Be manufactured using the same materials and processes\n- Have the same overlap as used in the regulated structure. No scaling is permitted.\nc. The force and displacement data and photos of the test setup must be included in the SES.\nd. The shear strength of the bond must be more than the UTS of the skin\n\n\n# F.4.4 Equivalent Flat Panel Calculation \n\nF.4.4.1 When specified, the Equivalence of the chassis must be calculated as a flat panel with the same composition as the chassis about the neutral axis of the laminate.\nF.4.4.2 The curvature of the panel and geometric cross section of the chassis must be ignored for these calculations.\nF.4.4.3 Calculations of Equivalence that do not reference this section F.4.4 may use the actual geometry of the chassis.\n\n## F. 5 CHASSIS REQUIREMENTS\n\nThis section applies to all Chassis, regardless of material or construction', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=30, markdown='# F.5.1 Primary Structure \n\nF.5.1.1 The Primary Structure must be constructed from one or a combination of the following:\n\n- Steel Tubing and Material\nF.3.2 F.3.4\n- Alternative Tubing Materials\nF.3.2 F.3.5\n- Composite Material\nF. 4\nF.5.1.2 Any chassis design that combines the Tube Frame, Monocoque, tubing and/or composite types must:\na. The support tube must terminate at a node of the chassis\nc. Be attached at a Hoop to Brace node or a fully Triangulated structural node without the ability to create a moment at the node\nb. When not attached at a node as described above, then:\n- Additional Structural bracing meeting F.3.2.1.o must be added to prevent bending loads\n- Additional calculations must be performed to show the member will not fail in bending or shear, even if unbraced\nF.5.11.3 External Items should not point at the driver\n\n\n## F.5.12 Mechanically Attached Roll Hoop Bracing\n\nF.5.12.1 When Roll Hoop Bracing is mechanically attached:\na. Fully Triangulated structure with tubes meeting F.3.2.1.n\nb. Structure Equivalent to the above, as determined per F.4.1.3\n\n## F. 6 TUBE FRAMES\n\n## F.6.1 Front Bulkhead\n\nThe Front Bulkhead must be constructed of closed section tubing meeting F.3.2.1.a\n\n## F.6.2 Front Bulkhead Support\n\nF.6.2.1 Frame Members of the Front Bulkhead Support system must be constructed of closed section tubing meeting F.3.2.1.b\nF.6.2.2 The Front Bulkhead must be securely integrated into the Frame.\nF.6.2.3 The Front Bulkhead must be supported back to the Front Hoop by a minimum of three Frame Members on each side of the vehicle; an upper member; lower member and diagonal brace to provide Triangulation.\na. The upper support member must be attached 50 mm or less from the top surface of the Front Bulkhead, and attach to the Front Hoop inside a zone extending 100 mm above and 50 mm below the Upper Side Impact member.\nb. If the upper support member is further than 100 mm above the Upper Side Impact member, then properly Triangulated bracing is required to transfer load to the Main Hoop by one of:\n\n- the Upper Side Impact member\n- an additional member transmitting load from the junction of the Upper Support Member with the Front Hoop\nc. The lower support member must be attached to the base of the Front Bulkhead and the base of the Front Hoop.\nd. The diagonal brace must properly Triangulate the upper and lower support members", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=37, markdown="F.6.2.4 Each of the above members may be multiple or bent tubes provided the requirements of F.5.2 are met.\nF.6.2.5 Examples of acceptable configurations of members may be found in the SES\n\n# F.6.3 Front Hoop Bracing \n\nF.6.3.1 Front Hoop Braces must be constructed of material meeting F.3.2.1.d\nF.6.3.2 The Front Hoop must be supported by two Braces extending in the forward direction, one on each of the left and right sides of the Front Hoop.\nF.6.3.3 The Front Hoop Braces must be constructed to protect the driver's legs and should extend to the structure in front of the driver's feet.\nF.6.3.4 The Front Hoop Braces must be attached as near as possible to the top of the Front Hoop but not more than 50 mm below the top-most surface of the Front Hoop. See figure following F.5.9.6 above\nF.6.3.5 If the Front Hoop above the Upper Side Impact Structure leans rearwards by more than $10^{\\circ}$ from the vertical, it must be supported by additional rearward Front Hoop Braces to a fully Triangulated structural node.\nF.6.3.6 The Front Hoop Braces must be straight, without any bends\n\n## F.6.4 Side Impact Structure\n\nF.6.4.1 Frame Members of the Side Impact Structure must be constructed of closed section tubing meeting F.3.2.1.e or F.3.2.1.f, as applicable\nF.6.4.2 With proper Triangulation, Side Impact Structure members may be fabricated from more than one piece of tubing.\nF.6.4.3 The Side Impact Structure must be comprised of three or more tubular members located on each side of the driver while seated in the normal driving position\n![img-11.jpeg](img-11.jpeg)\nF.6.4.4 The Upper Side Impact Member must:\na. Connect the Main Hoop and the Front Hoop.\nb. Be entirely in a zone that is parallel to the ground between 240 mm and 320 mm above the lowest point of the top surface of the Lower Side Impact Member\nF.6.4.5 The Lower Side Impact Structure member must connect the bottom of the Main Hoop and the bottom of the Front Hoop.", images=[OCRImageObject(id='img-11.jpeg', top_left_x=328, top_left_y=1212, bottom_right_x=1343, bottom_right_y=1663, image_base64='data:image/jpeg;base64,', image_annotation='{\n  "image_type": "Diagram",\n  "short_description": "A diagram showing the impact members of a vehicle\'s side structure.",\n  "summary": "The image is a detailed diagram illustrating the impact members of a vehicle\'s side structure. Examples of acceptable configurations of members may be found in the SES.\n\n## F. 7 MONOCOQUE\n\n## F.7.1 General Requirements\n\nF.7.1.1 The Structural Equivalency Spreadsheet must show that the design is Equivalent to a welded frame in terms of energy dissipation, yield and ultimate strengths in bending, buckling and tension\nF.7.1.2 Composite and metallic monocoques have the same requirements\nF.7.1.3 Corners between panels used for structural equivalence must contain core\nF.7.1.4 An inspection hole approximately 4 mm in diameter must be drilled through a low stress location of every monocoque section regulated by the Structural Equivalency Spreadsheet This inspection hole is not required in the Vertical Side Impact Structure F.7.5.3.b", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=39, markdown='# F.7.1.5 Composite monocoques must: \n\na. Meet the materials requirements in F. 4 Composite and Other Materials\nb. Use data from the laminate testing results as the basis for any strength or stiffness calculations\n\n## F.7.2 Front Bulkhead\n\nF.7.2.1 When modeled as an "L" shaped section the EI of the Front Bulkhead about both vertical and lateral axis must be equivalent to that of the tubes specified for the Front Bulkhead per F.6.1\nF.7.2.2 The length of the section perpendicular to the Front Bulkhead may be a maximum of 25 mm measured from the rearmost face of the Front Bulkhead\nF.7.2.3 Any Front Bulkhead which supports the IA plate must have a perimeter shear strength equivalent to a 1.5 mm thick steel plate\n\n## F.7.3 Front Bulkhead Support\n\nF.7.3.1 In addition to proving that the strength of the monocoque is sufficient, the monocoque must have equivalent EI to the sum of the EI of the six Steel Tubes (F.3.2.1.b) that it replaces.\nF.7.3.2 The EI of the vertical side of the Front Bulkhead support structure must be equivalent to or more than the EI of one steel tube that it replaces when calculated as per F.4.4\nF.7.3.3 The perimeter shear strength of the monocoque laminate in the Front Bulkhead support structure must be 4 kN or more for a section with a diameter of 25 mm .\nThis must be proven by a physical test completed per F.4.3.5 and the results included in the SES.\n\n## F.7.4 Front Hoop Attachment\n\nF.7.4.1 The Front Hoop must be mechanically attached to the monocoque\na. Front Hoop Mounting Plates must be the minimum thickness of the Front Hoop F.3.2.1.c\nb. The Front Hoop tube must be mechanically connected to the Mounting Plate with Mounting Plates parallel to both sides of the tube, with gussets from the Front Hoop tube along both sides of the mounting plate\nF.7.4.2 Front Hoop attachment to a monocoque must obey F.5.7.2 or F.7.8 within 25 mm of any bends and nodes that are not at the top center of the Front Hoop\nF.7.4.3 The Front Hoop may be fully laminated into the monocoque if:\na. The Front Hoop has core fit tightly around its entire circumference. Expanding foam is not permitted\nb. Equivalence to six or more mounts compliant with F.7.8 must show in the SES\nc. Each attachment point for the Anti-Submarine Belts must support a minimum load of 15 kN before failure.\nd. If the Lap Belt and Anti-Submarine Belt mounting points are less than 125 mm apart, or are attached to the same attachment point, then each mounting point must support a minimum load of 30 kN before failure.\nF.7.9.2 Load Testing\n\nThe strength of Lap Belt, Shoulder Belt, and Anti-Submarine Belt attachments must be proven by physical tests where the required load is applied to a representative attachment point where the proposed layup and attachment bracket are used.\na. Edges of the test fixture supporting the sample must be a minimum of 125 mm from the load application point (load vector intersecting a plane)\nb. Test Load application of the Lap Belt and Anti Submarine Belts must be normal (90 degrees) to the plane of the test sample\nc. Shoulder Belt Test Load application must meet:\n\n| Installed Shoulder Belt Angle: | Test Load Application Angle must be: | should be: |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| Between $90^{\\circ}$ and $45^{\\circ}$ | Between $90^{\\circ}$ and the installed <br> Shoulder Belt Angle | $90^{\\circ}$ |\n| Between $45^{\\circ}$ and $0^{\\circ}$ | Between $90^{\\circ}$ and $45^{\\circ}$ | $90^{\\circ}$ |\n\nThe angles are measured from the plane of the Test Sample ( $90^{\\circ}$ is normal to the Test Sample and $0^{\\circ}$ is parallel to the Test Sample)\nd. The Shoulder Harness test sample must not be any larger than the section of the monocoque as built\ne. The width of the Shoulder Harness test sample must not be any wider than the Shoulder Harness "panel height" (see Structural Equivalency Spreadsheet) used to show equivalency for the Shoulder Harness mounting bar\nf. Designs with attachments near a free edge must not support the free edge during the test\n\nThe intent is that the test specimen, to the best extent possible, represents the vehicle as driven at competition. Teams are expected to test a panel that is manufactured in as close a configuration to what is built in the vehicle as possible\n\n# F. 8 FRONT CHASSIS PROTECTION \n\n## F.8.1 Requirements\n\nF.8.1.1 Forward of the Front Bulkhead there must be an Impact Attenuator with an Anti Intrusion Plate between the Impact Attenuator and the Front Bulkhead.\nF.8.1.2 All methods of attachment of the Impact Attenuator to the Anti Intrusion Plate, and of the Anti Intrusion Plate to the Front Bulkhead must provide sufficient load paths for transverse and vertical loads if off-axis impacts occur.\n\n## F.8.2 Anti Intrusion Plate - AIP\n\nF.8.2.1 The Anti Intrusion Plate must be one of the following:\na. 1.5 mm minimum thickness solid steel\nb. 4.0 mm minimum thickness solid aluminum plate', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=43, markdown='c. Composite material per F.8.3\nF.8.2.2 The outside profile requirement of the Anti Intrusion Plate depends on the method of attachment to the Front Bulkhead:\na. Welded joints: the profile must align with or be more than the centerline of the Front Bulkhead tubes on all sides\nb. Bolted joints, bonding, laminating: the profile must align with or be more than the outside dimensions of the Front Bulkhead around the entire periphery\nF.8.2.3 Attachment of the Anti Intrusion Plate directly to the Front Bulkhead must be documented in the team\'s SES submission. The accepted methods of attachment are:\na. Welding\n\n- All weld lengths must be 25 mm or longer\n- If interrupted, the weld/space ratio must be 1:1 or higher\nb. Bolted joints\n- Using no less than eight 8 mm or 5/16" minimum diameter Critical Fasteners, T.8.2.\n- The distance between any two bolt centers must be 50 mm minimum.\n- Each bolt attachment must have pullout, tearout and bending capabilities of 15 kN\nc. Bonding\n- The Front Bulkhead must have no openings\n- The entire surface of the Anti Intrusion Plate must be bonded, with shear and peel strength higher than 120 kN\nd. Laminating\n- The Anti Intrusion Plate must be in front of the outer skin of the Front Bulkhead\n- The lamination must fully enclose the Anti Intrusion Plate and have shear capability higher than 120 kN\n\n\n# F.8.3 Composite Anti Intrusion Plate \n\nF.8.3.1 Composite Anti Intrusion Plates:\na. Must not fail in a frontal impact\nb. Must withstand a minimum static load of 120 kN distributed over the $200 \\mathrm{~mm} \\times 100 \\mathrm{~mm}$ minimum Impact Attenuator area\nF.8.3.2 Strength of the Composite Anti Intrusion Plate must be verified by one of the two methods:\na. Physical testing of the AIP attached to a structurally representative section of the intended chassis\n\n- The test fixture must have equivalent strength and stiffness to a baseline front bulkhead or must be the same as the first 50 mm of the Chassis\n- Test data is valid for only one Competition Year\nb. Laminate material testing under F.4.3.2 and F.4.3.5 and calculations of 3 point bending and perimeter shear', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=44, markdown='# F.8.4 Impact Attenuator - IA \n\nF.8.4.1 Teams must do one of:\n\n- Use an approved Standard Impact Attenuator from the FSAE Online Website\n- Build and test a Custom Impact Attenuator of their own design F.8.8\nF.8.4.2 The Custom Impact Attenuator must meet the following:\na. Length 200 mm or more, with its length oriented along the fore/aft axis of the Chassis.\nb. Minimum height 100 mm (perpendicular to the ground) and minimum width 200 mm (parallel to the ground) for a minimum distance of 200 mm forward of the Front Bulkhead.\nc. Segmented foam attenuators must have all segments bonded together to prevent sliding or parallelogramming.\nd. Honeycomb attenuators made of multiple segments must have a continuous panel between each segment.\nF.8.4.3 If the outside profile of the Front Bulkhead is more than $400 \\mathrm{~mm} \\times 350 \\mathrm{~mm}$, or the team uses the Standard Honeycomb Impact Attenuator, and then one of the two must be met:\na. The Front Bulkhead must include an additional support that is a diagonal or X-brace that meets F.3.2.1.b or Equivalent (integral or attached) for Monocoque bulkheads F.2.3.1\n- The structure must go across the entire Front Bulkhead opening on the diagonal\n- Attachment points at both ends must carry a minimum load of 30 kN in any direction\nb. Physical testing per F.8.8.6 and F.8.8.7 must be performed to prove that the Anti Intrusion Plate does not permanently deflect more than 25 mm .\n\n\n## F.8.5 Impact Attenuator Attachment\n\nF.8.5.1 The attachment of the Impact Attenuator to the Anti Intrusion Plate or Front Bulkhead must be documented in the SES submission\nF.8.5.2 The Impact Attenuator must attach with an approved method:\n\n| Impact Attenuator Type |  | Construction | Attachment Method(s): |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| a. | Standard or Custom | Foam, Honeycomb | Bonding |\n| b. | Custom | other | Bonding, Welding, Bolting |\n\nF.8.5.3 If the Impact Attenuator is attached by bonding:\na. Bonding must meet F.5.5\nb. The shear strength of the bond must be higher than:\n\n- 95 kN for foam Impact Attenuators\n- 38.5 kN for honeycomb Impact Attenuators\n- The maximum compressive force for custom Impact Attenuators\nc. The entire surface of a foam Impact Attenuator must be bonded\nd. Only the pre-crushed area of a honeycomb Impact Attenuator may be used for bond equivalence\nF.8.5.4 If the Impact Attenuator is attached by welding:\na. Welds may be continuous or interrupted', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=45, markdown='b. If interrupted, the weld/space ratio must be 1:1 or higher\nc. All weld lengths must be more than 25 mm\nF.8.5.5 If the Impact Attenuator is attached by bolting:\na. Must have no less than eight 8 mm or $5 / 16^{\\prime \\prime}$ minimum diameter Critical Fasteners, T.8.2\nb. The distance between any two bolt centers must be 50 mm minimum\nc. Each bolt attachment must have pullout, tearout and bending capabilities of 15 kN\nd. Must be bolted directly to the Primary Structure\nF.8.5.6 Impact Attenuator Position\na. All Impact Attenuators must mount with the bottom leading edge no more than 220 mm above the lowest point on the top of the Lower Side Impact Structure\nb. A Custom Impact Attenuator must mount with an area of 200 mm or more long and 200 mm or more wide that intersects a plane parallel to the ground that is no more than 220 mm above the lowest point on the top of the Lower Side Impact Structure\nF.8.5.7 Impact Attenuator Orientation\na. The Impact Attenuator must be centered laterally on the Front Bulkhead\nb. Standard Honeycomb must be mounted 200 mm width $\\times 100 \\mathrm{~mm}$ height\nc. Standard Foam may be mounted laterally or vertically\n\n# F.8.6 Front Impact Objects \n\nF.8.6.1 The only items allowed forward of the Anti Intrusion Plate in front view are the Impact Attenuator, fastener heads, and light bodywork / nosecones\n\nFasteners should be oriented with the nuts rearwards\nF.8.6.2 Front Wing and Bodywork Attachment\na. The front wing and front wing mounts must be able to move completely aft of the Anti Intrusion Plate and not touch the front bulkhead during a frontal impact\nb. The attachment points for the front wing and bodywork mounts should be aft of the Anti Intrusion Plate\nc. Tabs for wing and bodywork attachment must not extend more than 25 mm forward of the Anti Intrusion Plate\nF.8.6.3 Pedal assembly at full travel and adjustment must have a minimum 25 mm clearance to the:\na. Rear face of the Anti Intrusion Plate\nb. All Front Bulkhead structure F.6.1, F.7.2, F.8.4.3\nc. All Non Crushable Items inside the Primary Structure\n\nNon Crushable Items include, but are not limited to batteries, master cylinders, hydraulic reservoirs\n\n## F.8.7 Front Impact Verification\n\nF.8.7.1 The combination of the Impact Attenuator assembly and the force to crush or detach all other items forward of the Anti Intrusion plate must not exceed the peak deceleration specified in F.8.8.2\n\nIgnore light bodywork, light nosecones, and outboard wheel assemblies', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=46, markdown='F.8.7.2 The peak load for the type of Impact Attenuator:\n\n- Standard Foam Impact Attenuator 95 kN\n- Standard Honeycomb Impact Attenuator 60 kN\n- Tested Impact Attenuator peak as measured\nF.8.7.3 Use the Test Method F.8.7.4 or the Calculation Method F.8.7.5 to prove the force requirement\nF.8.7.4 Test Method\n\nGet the peak force from physical testing of the Impact Attenuator and any Non Crushable Object(s) as one of the two:\na. Tested together with the Impact Attenuator\nb. Tested with the Impact Attenuator not attached, and add the peak load from F.8.7.2\nF.8.7.5 Calculation Method\na. Calculate a failure load for the mounting of the Non Crushable Object(s) from fastener shear, tearout, and/or link buckling\nb. Add the peak attenuator load from F.8.7.2\nF.8.8 Impact Attenuator Data - IAD\nF.8.8.1 All teams must include an Impact Attenuator Data (IAD) report as part of the SES.\nF.8.8.2 Impact Attenuator Functional Requirements\n\nThese are not test requirements\na. Decelerates the vehicle at a rate not exceeding 20 g average and 40 g peak\nb. Energy absorbed must be more than 7350 J\n\nWhen:\n\n- Total mass of Vehicle is 300 kg\n- Impact velocity is $7.0 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$\nF.8.8.3 When using the Standard Impact Attenuator, the SES must meet the following:\na. Test data will not be submitted\nb. All other requirements of this section must be included.\nc. Photos of the actual attenuator must be included\nd. Evidence that the Standard IA meets the design criteria provided in the Standard Impact Attenuator specification must be included with the SES. This may be a receipt or packing slip from the supplier.\nF.8.8.4 The Impact Attenuator Data Report when NOT using the Standard Impact Attenuator must include:\na. Test data that proves that the Impact Attenuator Assembly meets the Functional Requirements F.8.8.2\nb. Calculations showing how the reported absorbed energy and decelerations have been derived.\nc. A schematic of the test method.\nd. Photos of the attenuator, annotated with the height of the attenuator before and after testing.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=47, markdown='F.8.8.5 The Impact Attenuator Test is valid for only one Competition Year\nF.8.8.6 Impact Attenuator Test Setup\na. During any test, the Impact Attenuator must be attached to the Anti Intrusion Plate using the intended vehicle attachment method.\nb. The Impact Attenuator Assembly must be attached to a structurally representative section of the intended chassis.\n\nThe test fixture must have equivalent strength and stiffness to a baseline front bulkhead. A solid block of material in the shape of the front bulkhead is not "structurally representative".\nc. There must be 50 mm minimum clearance rearwards of the Anti Intrusion Plate to the test fixture.\nd. No part of the Anti Intrusion Plate may permanently deflect more than 25 mm beyond the position of the Anti Intrusion Plate before the test.\nThe 25 mm spacing represents the front bulkhead support and insures that the plate does not intrude excessively into the cockpit.\nF.8.8.7 Test Conduct\na. Composite Impact Attenuators must be Dynamic Tested.\n\nOther Impact Attenuator constructions may be Dynamic Tested or Quasi-Static Tested\nb. Dynamic Testing (sled, pendulum, drop tower, etc.) of the Impact Attenuator must be conducted at a dedicated test facility. This facility may be part of the University, but must be supervised by professional staff or the University faculty. Teams must not construct their own dynamic test apparatus.\nc. Quasi-Static Testing may be performed by teams using their University\'s facilities/equipment, but teams are advised to exercise due care when performing all tests.\nF.8.8.8 Test Analysis\na. When using acceleration data from the dynamic test, the average deceleration must be calculated based on the raw unfiltered data.\nb. If peaks above the 40 g limit are present in the data, a Channel Filter Class (CFC) 60 (100Hz) filter per SAE Recommended Practice J211 "Instrumentation for Impact Test", or a $100 \\mathrm{~Hz}, 3 \\mathrm{rd}$ order, low pass Butterworth ( -3 dB at 100 Hz ) filter may be applied.\n\n# F. 9 FUEL SYSTEM (IC ONLY) \n\nFuel System Location and Protection are subject to approval during SES review and Technical Inspection.\n\n## F.9.1 Location\n\nF.9.1.1 Any portion of the Fuel System that is less than 350 mm above the ground, and all parts of the Fuel Tank, must be inside the Primary Structure (F.1.10).\nF.9.1.2 In side view, any portion of the Fuel System must not project below the lower surface of the chassis\n\n## F.9.2 Protection\n\nAll Fuel Tanks must be shielded from side or rear impact', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=48, markdown='# F. 10 ACCUMULATOR CONTAINER (EV ONLY) \n\n## F.10.1 General Requirements\n\nF.10.1.1 All Accumulator Containers must be:\na. Designed to withstand forces from deceleration in all directions\nb. Made from a Nonflammable Material ( F.1.18)\nF.10.1.2 Design of the Accumulator Container must be documented in the SES.\n\nDocumentation includes materials used, drawings/images, fastener locations, cell/segment weight and cell/segment position.\nF.10.1.3 The Accumulator Containers and mounting systems are subject to approval during SES review and Technical Inspection\nF.10.1.4 If the Accumulator Container is not constructed from steel or aluminum, the material properties should be established at a temperature of $60^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$\nF.10.1.5 If adhesives are used for credited bonding, the bond performance should be established at a temperature of $60^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$\n\n## F.10.2 External Structure\n\nF.10.2.1 The Floor or Bottom must be made from one of the three:\na. Internal vertical walls separating cells and/or segments:\n\n- Must have minimum height of the full height of the Accumulator Segments\n- Should extend to the lid above any segment\nc. Must not have line of sight to the driver, with the Firewall installed or removed\n\n# F.10.5 Attachment \n\nF.10.5.1 Attachment of the Accumulator Container must be documented in the SES\nF.10.5.2 Accumulator Containers must:\na. Eight or more attachments are required for any configuration.\n- One attachment for each corner of a rectangular structure of multiple Accumulator Segments\n- More than the minimum number of fasteners may be required for non rectangular arrangements\n\nExamples: If not filled in with additional structure, an extruded L shape would require attachments at 10 convex corners (the corners at the inside of the L are not convex); an extruded hexagon would require 12 attachments\nb.
