The voltage in the Tractive System must be Low Voltage T.9.1.2 in five seconds or less\nd. The Motor(s) must spin free. Torque must not be applied to the Motor(s)\nEV.7.2.3 When the AMS, IMD or BSPD Open the Shutdown Circuit:\na. The Tractive System must stay disabled until manually reset\nb. The Tractive System must be reset only by manual action of a person directly at the vehicle\nc. The driver must not be able to reactivate the Tractive System from inside the vehicle\nd. Operation of the Shutdown Buttons or TSMS must not reset the Shutdown Circuit\nEV.7.2.4 The driver may reset the Shutdown Circuit from the cockpit, subject to EV.7.2.3\n\n# EV.7.3 Accumulator Management System - AMS \n\nEV.7.3.1 An Accumulator Management System must monitor the Accumulator(s) Voltage EV.7.4 and Temperature EV.7.5 when the:\na. Tractive System is Active EV.11.5\nb. Accumulator is connected to a Charger EV.8.3\nEV.7.3.2 The AMS must have galvanic isolation at every segment to segment boundary, as approved in the ESF\nEV.7.3.3 Cell balancing is not permitted when the Shutdown Circuit is Open (EV.7.2, EV.8.4)\nEV.7.3.4 The AMS must monitor for:\na. Voltage values outside the allowable range EV.7.4.2\nb. Voltage sense Overcurrent Protection device(s) blown or tripped\nc. Temperature values outside the allowable range EV.7.5.2\nd. Missing or interrupted voltage or temperature measurements\ne. A fault in the AMS\nEV.7.3.5 If the AMS detects one or more of the conditions of EV.7.3.4 above, the AMS must:\na. Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2\nb. Turn on the AMS Indicator Light. The light must stay on until the AMS is reset EV.7.2.3\nEV.7.3.6 The AMS Indicator Light must be:\na. Color: Red\nb. Clearly visible to the seated driver in bright sunlight\nc. Clearly marked with the lettering "AMS"\n\n## EV.7.4 Accumulator Voltage\n\nEV.7.4.1 The AMS must measure the cell voltage of every cell\nWhen single cells are directly connected in parallel, only one voltage measurement is needed\nEV.7.4.2 Cell Voltage levels must stay inside the allowed minimum and maximum cell voltage levels stated in the cell data sheet. Measurement accuracy must be considered.\nEV.7.4.3 All voltage sense wires to the AMS must meet one of:\na. Have Overcurrent Protection EV.7.4.4 below\nb. Meet requirements for no Overcurrent Protection listed in EV.7.4.5 below', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=102, markdown='EV.7.4.4 When used, Overcurrent Protection for the AMS voltage sense wires must meet the following.\na. The Overcurrent Protection must occur in the conductor, wire or PCB trace which is directly connected to the cell tab.\nb. The voltage rating of the Overcurrent Protection must be equal to or higher than the maximum segment voltage\n\nEV.7.4.5 Overcurrent Protection is not required on a voltage sense wire if all three of the following conditions are met:\n\n- AMS is a distributed AMS system (one cell measurement per board)\n- $\\quad$ Sense wire length is less than 25 mm\n- AMS board has Overcurrent Protection\n\n\n# EV.7.5 Accumulator Temperature \n\nEV.7.5.1 The AMS must measure the temperatures of critical points of the Accumulator\nEV.7.5.2 Temperatures (considering measurement accuracy) must stay below the lower of the two:\n\n- The maximum cell temperature limit stated in the cell data sheet\n- $60^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$\n\nEV.7.5.3 Cell temperatures must be measured at the negative terminal of the respective cell\nEV.7.5.4 The temperature sensor used must be in direct contact with one of:\n\n- The negative terminal itself\n- The negative terminal busbar less than 10 mm away from the cell terminal\n\nEV.7.5.5 For lithium based cells,\na. The temperature of a minimum of $20 \\%$ of the cells must be monitored by the AMS\nb. The monitored cells must be equally distributed inside the Accumulator Container(s) Every cell temperature should be monitored\n\nEV.7.5.6 Multiple cells may be monitored with one temperature sensor, if EV.7.5 is met for all cells sensed by the sensor.\n\nEV.7.5.7 Temperature sensors must have appropriate electrical isolation that meets one of the two:\n\n- Between the sensor and cell\n- In the sensing circuit\n\nThe isolation must consider both GLV/TS isolation as well as common mode voltages between sense locations.\n\n## EV.7.6 Insulation Monitoring Device - IMD\n\nEV.7.6.1 The vehicle must have an Insulation Monitoring Device (IMD) installed in the Tractive System\nEV.7.6.2 The IMD must be a Bender ISOMETER ${ }^{\\circledR}$ IR155-3203 or IR155-3204 (website) or an approved alternate equivalent IMD\n\nRefer to the Rules FAQ on the FSAE Online website for approved equivalent IMD\nEV.7.6.3 The response value of the IMD must be set to 500 Ohm / Volt or higher, related to the maximum Tractive System operation voltage.\n\nEV.7.6.4 The IMD must monitor the Tractive System for:\na. An isolation failure', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=103, markdown='b. A failure in the IMD operation\n\nThis must be done without the influence of any programmable logic.\nEV.7.6.5 If the IMD detects one or more of the conditions of EV.7.6.4 above the IMD must:\na. Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2\nb. Turn on the IMD Indicator Light. The light must stay on until the IMD is reset EV.7.2.3\nEV.7.6.6 The IMD Indicator Light must be:\na. Color: Red\nb. Clearly visible to the seated driver in bright sunlight\nc. Clearly marked with the lettering "IMD"\n\n# EV.7.7 Brake System Plausibility Device - BSPD \n\nEV.7.7.1 The vehicle must have a standalone nonprogrammable circuit to check for simultaneous braking and high power output\nThe BSPD must be provided in addition to the APPS / Brake Pedal Plausibility Check (EV.4.7)\nEV.7.7.2 The BSPD must Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2 when the two of these exist:\n\n- Demand for Hard Braking EV.4.6\n- Motor/Accumulator current is at a level where 5 kW of electrical power in the DC circuit is delivered to the Motor(s) at the nominal battery voltage\nThe BSPD may delay opening the shutdown circuit up to 0.5 sec to avoid false trips\nEV.7.7.3 The BSPD must Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2 when there is an open or short circuit in any sensor input\nEV.7.7.4 The team must have a test to demonstrate BSPD operation at Electrical Technical Inspection.\na. Power must not be sent to the Motor(s) of the vehicle during the test\nb. The test must prove the function of the complete BSPD in the vehicle, including the current sensor\n\nThe suggested test would introduce a current by a separate wire from an external power supply simulating the Tractive System current while pressing the brake pedal\n\n## EV.7.8 Interlocks\n\nEV.7.8.1 Interlocks must be incorporated where specified (refer to EV.4.1.3, EV.5.5.2, EV.5.10)\nEV.7.8.2 Additional Interlocks may be included in the Tractive System or components\nEV.7.8.3 The Interlock is a wire or connection that must:\na. Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2 if the Interlock connection is broken or interrupted\nb. Not be in the low (ground) connection to the AIR coils of the Shutdown Circuit\nEV.7.8.4 Interlock circuits or connections do not require physical separation (EV.6.5) from Tractive System wiring or components\n\n## EV.7.9 Master Switches\n\nEV.7.9.1 Each vehicle must have two Master Switches that must:\na. Meet T.9.3 for Configuration and Location\nb. Be direct acting, not act through a relay or logic', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=104, markdown='EV.7.9.2 The Grounded Low Voltage Master Switch (GLVMS) must:\na. Completely stop all power to the GLV System EV.4.4\nb. Be in the center of a completely red circular area of $>50 \\mathrm{~mm}$ in diameter\nc. Be labeled "LV"\n\nEV.7.9.3 The Tractive System Master Switch (TSMS) must:\na. Open the Shutdown Circuit in the OFF position EV.7.2.2\nb. Be the last switch before the AIRs except for Precharge circuitry and Interlocks.\nc. Be in the center of a completely orange circular area of $>50 \\mathrm{~mm}$ in diameter\nd. Be labeled "TS" and the symbol specified in ISO 7010-W012 (triangle with black lightning bolt on yellow background).\ne. Be fitted with a "lockout/tagout" capability in the OFF position EV.11.3.1\n\n# EV.7.10 Shutdown Buttons \n\nEV.7.10.1 Three Shutdown Buttons must be installed on the vehicle.\nEV.7.10.2 Each Shutdown Button must be a push-pull or push-rotate emergency switch\nEV.7.10.3 One Shutdown Button must be on each side of the vehicle which:\na. Is located aft of the driver\'s compartment at approximately the level of the driver\'s head\nb. Has a diameter of 40 mm minimum\nc. Must not be easily removable or mounted onto removable body work\n\nEV.7.10.4 One Shutdown Button must be mounted in the cockpit which:\na. Is located in easy reach of the belted in driver, adjacent to the steering wheel, and unobstructed by the steering wheel or any other part of the vehicle\nb. Has diameter of 24 mm minimum\n\nEV.7.10.5 The international electrical symbol (a red spark on a white edged blue triangle) must be near each Shutdown Button.\nEV.7.10.6 Pressing any of the Shutdown Buttons must Open the Shutdown Circuit EV.7.2.2\n\n## EV. 8 CHARGER REQUIREMENTS\n\n## EV.8.1 Charger Requirements\n\nEV.8.1.1 All features and functions of the Charger and Charging Shutdown Circuit must be demonstrated at Electrical Technical Inspection. IN.4.1\nEV.8.1.2 Chargers will be sealed after approval. IN.4.7.1\n\n## EV.8.2 Charger Features\n\nEV.8.2.1 The Charger must be galvanically isolated (AC) input to (DC) output.\nEV.8.2.2 If the Charger housing is conductive it must be connected to the earth ground of the AC input.\nEV.8.2.3 All connections of the Charger(s) must be isolated and covered.\nEV.8.2.4 The Charger connector(s) must incorporate a feature to let the connector become live only when correctly connected to the Accumulator.\nEV.8.2.5 High Voltage charging leads must be orange\nEV.8.2.6 The Charger must have two TSMPs installed, see EV.5.8.2', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=105, markdown='EV.8.2.7 The Charger must include a Charger Shutdown Button which is:\na. A push-pull or push-rotate emergency switch\nb. Minimum diameter of 25 mm\nc. Labelled with the international electrical symbol $\\underline{Y}$ (a red spark on a white edged blue triangle)\n\n# EV.8.3 Charging Shutdown Circuit \n\nEV.8.3.1 The Charging Shutdown Circuit consists of:\na. Charger Shutdown Button EV.8.2.7\nb. Accumulator Management System (AMS) EV.7.3\nc. Insulation Monitoring Device (IMD) EV.7.6\nEV.8.3.2 The AMS and IMD parts of the Charging Shutdown Circuit must:\na. Be designed as Normally Open contacts\nb. Have completely independent circuits to Open the Charging Shutdown Circuit. Design of the respective circuits must ensure that a failure cannot result in electrical power being fed back into the Charging Shutdown Circuit.\n\n## EV.8.4 Charging Shutdown Circuit Operation\n\nEV.8.4.1 When Charging, the AMS and IMD must:\na. Monitor the Accumulator\nb. Open the Charging Shutdown Circuit if a fault is detected.\n\nEV.8.4.2 When the Charging Shutdown Circuit Opens:\na. All current flow to the Accumulator must stop immediately\nb. The voltage in the Tractive System must be Low Voltage T.9.1.2 in five seconds or less\nc. The Charger must be turned off\nd. The Charger must stay disabled until manually reset\n\n## EV. 9 VEHICLE OPERATIONS\n\n## EV.9.1 Activation Sequence\n\nThe vehicle systems must energize in the following sequence:\na. Low Voltage (GLV) System EV.9.2\nb. Tractive System Active EV.9.3\nc. Ready to Drive EV.9.4\n\n## EV.9.2 Low Voltage (GLV) System\n\nThe Shutdown Circuit may be Closed when or after the GLV System is energized EV.7.2.4\n\n## EV.9.3 Tractive System Active\n\nEV.9.3.1 Definition - High Voltage is present outside of the Accumulator Container\nEV.9.3.2 Tractive System Active must not be possible until both:\n\n- GLV System is Energized\n- Shutdown Circuit is Closed', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=106, markdown='# EV.9.4 Ready to Drive \n\nEV.9.4.1 Definition - the Motor(s) will respond to the input of the APPS\nEV.9.4.2 Ready to Drive must not be possible until the three at the same time:\n\n- $\\quad$ Tractive System Active EV.9.3\n- $\\quad$ The Brake Pedal is pressed and held to engage the mechanical brakes T.3.2\n- $\\quad$ The driver performs a manual action to initiate Ready to Drive Such as pressing a specific button in the cockpit\n\n\n## EV.9.5 Ready to Drive Sound\n\nEV.9.5.1 The vehicle must make a characteristic sound when it is Ready to Drive\nEV.9.5.2 The Ready to Drive Sound must be:\na. Sounded continuously for minimum 1 second and maximum 3 seconds\nb. A minimum sound level of 80 dBA , fast weighting IN.4.6\nc. Easily recognizable. No animal voices, song parts or sounds that could be interpreted as offensive will be accepted\n\nEV.9.5.3 The vehicle must not make other sounds similar to the Ready to Drive Sound.\n\n## EV. 10 EVENT SITE ACTIVITIES\n\n## EV.10.1 Onsite Registration\n\nEV.10.1.1 The Accumulator must be onsite at the time the team registers to be eligible for Accumulator Technical Inspection and Dynamic Events\nEV.10.1.2 Teams who register without the Accumulator:\na. Must not bring their Accumulator onsite for the duration of the competition\nb. May participate in Technical Inspection and Static Events\n\n## EV.10.2 Accumulator Removal\n\nEV.10.2.1 After the team registers onsite, the Accumulator must remain on the competition site until the end of the competition, or the team withdraws and leaves the site\nEV.10.2.2 Violators will be disqualified from the competition and must leave immediately\n\n## EV. 11 WORK PRACTICES\n\n## EV.11.1 Personnel\n\nEV.11.1.1 The Electrical System Officer (ESO): AD.5.2\na. Is the only person on the team that may declare the vehicle electrically safe to allow work on any system\nb. Must accompany the vehicle when operated or moved at the competition site\nc. Must be immediately available by phone at all times during the event\n\n## EV.11.2 Maintenance\n\nEV.11.2.1 All participating team members must wear safety glasses with side shields at any time when:\na. a label with the following data during Charging: Team name and Electrical System Officer phone number(s)\nEV.11.5.5 Additional site specific rules or policies may apply', images=[], Required\n\nEach vehicle must pass all applicable parts of Technical Inspection, receive Inspection Approval IN.13.1 and show the Inspection Sticker IN.13.2 before it may participate in any Dynamic event.\n\n## IN.1.2 Technical Inspection Authority\n\nIN.1.2.1 The exact procedures and instruments used for inspection and testing are entirely at the discretion of the Chief Technical active\nIN.4.4.2 The test passes if the IMD shuts down the Tractive System in 30 seconds or less at a fault resistance of $50 \\%$ below the response value corresponding to 250 Ohm / Volt\n\n## IN.4.5 The intent is to reduce the likelihood of wings detaching\nIN.8.2.2 If any deflection is significant, then a force of approximately 200 N may be applied.\na. Loaded deflection should not be more than 25 mm\nb. Any permanent deflection less than 5 mm\nIN.8.2.3 If any vehicle on track is observed to have large, uncontrolled movements of Aerodynamic Devices, then officials may Black Flag the vehicle for IN. 15 Reinspection.\n\n## IN.8.3 Monocoque Inspections\n\nIN.8.3.1 Dimensions of the Monocoque will be confirmed F.7.1.4\nIN.8.3.2 When the Front Hoop is integrally bonded or laminated to the monocoque F.7.4.3, provide:\na. The vehicle must contain the maximum amount of fluids it may carry\nb. The tallest driver must be seated in the normal driving position\nc. Tilt tests may be conducted in one or the other, or both directions in order to pass\nd. (IC only) Engines fitted with mechanically actuated fuel pumps must be run to fill and pressure the system downstream of the High Pressure pump. See IC.6.2\n\n## IN.9.2 Tilt Test Criteria\n\nIN.9.2.1 No fluid leakage of any type when the vehicle is tilted to a $45^{\\circ}$ angle to the horizontal\nIN.9.2.2 Vehicle does not roll when tilted at an angle of $60^{\\circ}$ to the horizontal, corresponding to 1.7 g .\n\n## IN.9.3 Tilt Test Completion\n\nTilt Tests must be passed before a vehicle may attempt any further inspections', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=113, markdown="# IN. 10 NOISE AND SWITCH TEST (IC ONLY) \n\n## IN.10.1 Sound Level Measurement\n\nIN.10.1.1 The sound level will be measured during a stationary test, with the vehicle gearbox in neutral at the defined Test Speed\nIN.10.1.2 Measurements will be made with a free field microphone placed:\n\n- free from obstructions\n- at the Exhaust Outlet vertical level IC.7.2.2\n- $\\quad 0.5 \\mathrm{~m}$ from the end of the Exhaust Outlet IC.7.2.2\n- at an angle of $45^{\\circ}$ with the outlet in the horizontal plane (see IN.10.2.2 below)\n\n\n## IN.10.2 Special Configurations\n\nIN.10.2.1 Where the Exhaust has more than one Exhaust Outlet:\na. Automotive / Motorcycle engines $914.4 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{min}(3,000 \\mathrm{ft} / \\mathrm{min})$\nb. Industrial Engines $731.5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{min}(2,400 \\mathrm{ft} / \\mathrm{min})$\n\nThe calculated speed will be rounded to the nearest 500 rpm .\nTest Speeds for typical engines are published on the FSAE Online website\nIN.10.4.2 Idle Test Speed\na. Determined by the vehicle's calibrated idle speed\nb. At idle 103 dBC, fast weighting\nb. At all other speeds 110 dBC, fast weighting\n\n## IN.10.6 Noise Level Retesting\n\nIN.10.6.1 Noise levels may be monitored at any time\nIN.10.6.2 The Noise Test may be repeated at any time\n\n## IN.10.7 Switch Function\n\nThe function of one or more of the Primary Master Switch IC.9.3, Cockpit Main Switch IC.9.4, and/or BOTS T.3.3 will be verified during the Noise Test\n\n## IN.10.8 Noise Test Completion\n\nNoise Tests must be passed before a vehicle may attempt any further inspections\n\n## IN. 11 RAIN TEST (EV ONLY)\n\n## IN.11.1 Rain Test Requirements\n\n- Tractive System must be Active\n- The vehicle must not be in Ready to Drive mode (EV.7)\n- Any driven wheels must not touch the ground\n- A driver must not be seated in the vehicle\n\n\n## IN.11.2 Rain Test Conduct\n\nThe water spray will be rain like, not a direct high pressure water jet\na. Spray water at the vehicle from any possible direction for 120 seconds\nb. Stop the water spray\nc. Observe the vehicle for 120 seconds\n\n## IN.11.3 Rain Test Completion\n\nThe test is passed if the Insulation Monitoring Device (EV.7.6) does not react during the entire 240 seconds duration\n\n## IN. 12 BRAKE TEST\n\n## IN.12.1 Objective\n\nThe brake system will be dynamically tested and must demonstrate the capability of locking all four wheels when stopping the vehicle in a straight line at the end of an acceleration run specified by the brake inspectors\n\n## IN.12.2 Brake Test Conduct (IC Only)\n\nIN.12.2.1 Brake Test procedure:\na. Accelerate to speed (typically getting into 2nd gear) until reaching the designated area\nb. Apply the brakes with force sufficient to demonstrate full lockup of all four wheels\nIN.12.2.2 The Brake Test passes if:\n\n- All four wheels lock up\n- The engine stays running during the complete test', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=115, markdown='# IN.12.3 Brake Test Conduct (EV Only) \n\nIN.12.3.1 Brake Test procedure:\na. Accelerate to speed until reaching the designated area\nb. Switch off the Tractive System\nc. Apply the brakes with force sufficient to demonstrate full lockup of all four wheels\nIN.12.3.2 The Brake Test passes if all four wheels lock while the Tractive System is shut down\nIN.12.3.3 The Tractive System Active Light may switch a short time after the vehicle has come to a complete stop as the reduction of the system voltage is not immediate. See EV.7.2.2.c\n\n## IN. 13 INSPECTION APPROVAL\n\n## IN.13.1 Inspection Approval\n\nIN.13.1.1 When all parts of Technical Inspection are complete as shown on the Technical Inspection sheet, the vehicle receives Inspection Approval\nIN.13.1.2 The completed Inspection Sticker denotes the Inspection Approval\nIN.13.1.3 The Inspection Approval is contingent on the vehicle remaining in the required condition throughout the competition.\nIN.13.1.4 The Organizer, Chief Technical Inspector, or a designee may void Inspection Approval at any time for any reason\n\n## IN.13.2 Inspection Sticker\n\nIN.13.2.1 Inspection Sticker(s) are issued following the completion of all or part of Technical Inspection\nIN.13.2.2 Inspection Sticker(s) must show in the location given in VE.1.4\n\n## IN.13.3 Inspection Validity\n\nIN.13.3.1 Inspection Stickers may be removed from vehicles that are not in compliance with the Rules or are required to be Reinspected.\nIN.13.3.2 Inspection Approval is valid only for the duration of the specific Formula SAE competition during which the inspection is conducted.\n\n## IN. 14 MODIFICATIONS AND REPAIRS\n\n## IN.14.1 Prior to Inspection Approval\n\nOnce the vehicle has been presented for judging in the Cost or Design Events, or submitted for Technical Inspection, and until the vehicle has the full Inspection Approval, the only modifications permitted to the vehicle are those directed by the Inspector(s) and noted on the Inspection Form.\n\n## IN.14.2 After Inspection Approval\n\nIN.14.2.1 The vehicle must maintain all required specifications (including but not limited to ride height, suspension travel, braking capacity (pad material/composition), sound level and wing location) throughout the competition.\nIN.14.2.2 Changes to fit the vehicle to different drivers are allowed. Permitted changes are:\n\n- Adjustment of the driver restraint system, Head Restraint, seat and pedal assembly\n- Substitution of the Head Restraint or seat insert\n- Adjustment of mirrors', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=116, markdown='IN.14.2.3 Once the vehicle receives Inspection Approval, the ONLY modifications permitted to the vehicle are the following:\n\n- Adjustment of belts, chains and clutches\n- Adjustment of brake bias\n- Adjustment to engine / powertrain operating parameters, including fuel mixture and ignition timing, and any software calibration changes\n- Adjustment of the suspension\n- Changing springs, sway bars and shims in the suspension\n- Adjustment of Tire Pressure, subject to V.4.3.4\n- Adjustment of wing or wing element(s) angle, but not the location T.7.1\n- Replenishment of fluids\n- Replacement of worn tires or brake pads. Replacement tires and brake pads must be identical in material/composition/size to those presented and approved at Technical Inspection.\n- Changing of wheels and tires for weather conditions D. 6\n- Recharging Low Voltage batteries\n- Recharging High Voltage Accumulators\n\n\n# IN.14.3 Repairs or Changes After Inspection Approval \n\nThe Inspection Approval may be voided for any reason including, but not limited to:\na. Damage to the vehicle IN.13.1.3\nb. Changes beyond those allowed per IN.14.2 above\n\n## IN. 15 REINSPECTION\n\n## IN.15.1 Requirement\n\nIN.15.1.1 Any vehicle may be Reinspected at any time for any reason\nIN.15.1.2 Reinspection must be completed to restore Inspection Approval, if voided\n\n## IN.15.2 Conduct\n\nIN.15.2.1 The Technical Inspection process may be repeated in entirety or in part\nIN.15.2.2 Specific areas or items to be inspected are at the discretion of the Chief Technical Inspector\n\n## IN.15.3 Result\n\nIN.15.3.1 With Voided Inspection Approval\nSuccessful completion of Reinspection will restore Inspection Approval IN.13.1\nIN.15.3.2 During Dynamic Events\na. Issues found during Reinspection will void Inspection Approval\nb. Penalties may be applied to the Dynamic Events the vehicle has competed in\n\nApplied penalties may include additional time added to event(s), loss of one or more fastest runs, up to DQ, subject to official discretion.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=117, markdown="# S - STATIC EVENTS \n\n### 5.1 GENERAL STATIC\n\nPresentation 75 points\nCost 100 points\nDesign 150 points\nTotal 325 points\n\n### 5.2 PRESENTATION EVENT\n\n### 5.2.1 Presentation Event Objective\n\nThe Presentation Event evaluates the team's ability to develop and deliver a comprehensive business, logistical, production, or technical case that will convince outside interests to invest in the team's concept.\n\n### 5.2.2 Presentation Concept\n\n5.2.2.1 The concept for the Presentation Event will be provided on the FSAE Online website.\n5.2.2.2 The concept for the Presentation Event may change for each competition\n5.2.2.3 The team presentation must meet the concept\n5.2.2.4 The team presentation must relate specifically to the vehicle as entered in the competition\n5.2.2.5 Teams should assume that the judges represent different areas, including engineering, production, marketing and finance, and may not all be engineers.\n5.2.2.6 The presentation may be given in different settings, such as a conference room, a group meeting, virtually, or in conjunction with other Static Events.\nSpecific details will be included in the Presentation Concept or communicated separately.\n\n### 5.2.3 Presentation Schedule\n\nTeams that fail to make their presentation during their assigned time period will receive zero points for the Presentation Event.\n\n### 5.2.4 Presentation Submissions\n\n5.2.4.1 The Presentation Concept may require information to be submitted prior to the event. Specific details will be included in the Presentation Concept.\n5.2.4.2 Submissions may be graded as part of the Presentation Event score.\n5.2.4.3 Pre event submissions will be subject to penalties imposed as given in section DR - Document Requirements.\n\n### 5.2.5 Presentation Format\n\n5.2.5.1 One or more team members will give the presentation to the judges.\n5.2.5.2 All team members who will give any part of the presentation, or who will respond to judges' questions must be:\n\n- In the presentation area when the presentation starts\n- Introduced and identified to the judges.\n5.2.5.3 Presentations will be time limited. The judges will stop any presentation exceeding the time limit.", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=118, markdown='5.2.5.4 The presentation itself will not be interrupted by questions. Immediately following the presentation there may be a question and answer session.\n5.2.5.5 Only judges may ask questions. Only team members who meet 5.2.5.2 may answer questions.\n\n# 5.2.6 Presentation Equipment \n\nTeams planning to use data projectors, visual display devices (tablets, computers, etc.), or other communication means as part of their presentation must bring, or arrange for, their own equipment.\n\n### 5.2.7 Evaluation Criteria\n\n5.2.7.1 Presentations will be evaluated on content, organization, visual aids, delivery and the team\'s response to the judges\' questions.\n5.2.7.2 The actual quality of the prototype itself will not be considered as part of the presentation judging\n5.2.7.3 Presentation Judging Score Sheet - available at the FSAE Online website.\n\n### 5.2.8 Judging Sequence\n\nPresentation judging may be conducted in one or more phases.\n\n### 5.2.9 Presentation Event Scoring\n\n5.2.9.1 The Presentation raw score is based on the average of the scores of each judge.\n5.2.9.2 Presentation Event scores may range from 0 to 75 points, using a method at the discretion of the judges\n5.2.9.3 Presentation Event scoring may include normalizing the scores of different judging teams and scaling the overall results.\n\n### 5.3 COST AND MANUFACTURING EVENT\n\n### 5.3.1 Cost Event Objective\n\nThe Cost and Manufacturing Event evaluates the ability of the team to consider budget and incorporate production considerations for production and efficiency.\nMaking tradeoff decisions between content and cost based on the performance of each part and assembly and accounting for each part and process to meet a budget is part of Project Management.\n\n### 5.3.2 Cost Event Supplement\n\na. Additional specific information on the Cost and Manufacturing Event, including explanation and requirements, is provided in the Formula SAE Cost Event Supplement document.\nb. Use the Formula SAE Cost Event Supplement to properly complete the requirements of the Cost and Manufacturing Event.\nc. The Formula SAE Cost Event Supplement is available on the FSAE Online website\n\n### 5.3.3 Cost Event Areas\n\n5.3.3.1 Cost Report\n\nPreparation and submission of a report (the "Cost Report")\n5.3.3.2 Event Day Discussion\n\nDiscussion at the Competition with the Cost Judges around the team\'s vehicle.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=119, markdown='# 5.3.3.3 Cost Scenario \n\nTeams will respond to a challenge related to cost or manufacturing of the vehicle.\n\n### 5.3.4 Cost Report\n\n5.3.4.1 The Cost Report must:\na. List and cost every part on the vehicle using the standardized Cost Tables.\nb. Base the cost on the actual manufacturing technique used on the prototype.\n\nCast parts on the prototype must be cost as cast, and fabricated parts as fabricated, etc.\nc. Include Tooling Cost (welding jigs, molds, patterns and dies) for processes requiring it.\nd. Exclude R \\& D and capital expenditures (plant, machinery, hand tools and power tools).\ne. Include supporting documentation to allow officials to verify part costing\n5.3.4.2 Generate and submit the Cost Report using the FSAE Online website, see DR - Document Requirements\n\n### 5.3.5 Bill of Materials - BOM\n\n5.3.5.1 The BOM is a list for every vehicle part, showing the relationships between the items.\na. The overall vehicle is broken down into separate Systems\nb. Systems are made up of Assemblies\nc. Assemblies are made up of Parts\nd. Parts consist of Materials, Processes and Fasteners\ne. Tooling is associated with each Process that requires production tooling\n\n### 5.3.6 Late Submission\n\nPenalties for Late Submission of Cost Report will be imposed as given in section DR Document Requirements.\n\n### 5.3.7 Cost Addendum\n\n5.3.7.1 A supplement to the Cost Report that reflects any changes or corrections made after the submission of the Cost Report may be submitted.\n5.3.7.2 The Cost Addendum must be submitted during Onsite Registration at the Event.\n5.3.7.3 The Cost Addendum must follow the format as given in section DR - Document Requirements\n5.3.7.4 Addenda apply only to the competition at which they are submitted.\n5.3.7.5 A separate Cost Addendum may be submitted for every competition a vehicle attends.\n5.3.7.6 Changes to the Cost Report in the Cost Addendum will incur additional cost:\na. Added items will be cost at $125 \\%$ of the table cost: + (1.25 x Cost)\nb. Removed items will be credited $75 \\%$ of the table cost: - ( $0.75 \\times$ Cost)\n\n### 5.3.8 Cost Tables\n\n5.3.8.1 All costs in the Cost Report must come from the standardized Cost Tables.\n5.3.8.2 If a team wishes to use any Parts, Processes or Materials not included in the tables, an Add Item Request must be submitted. See 5.3.10', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=120, markdown="# 5.3.9 Make versus Buy \n\n5.3.9.1 Every part may be classified as Made or Bought.\n\nRefer to the Formula SAE Cost Event Supplement for additional information\n5.3.9.2 If a team genuinely Makes a part listed on the table as a Bought part, they may alternatively cost it as a Made part only if a place holder entry is listed in the tables enabling them to do so.\n5.3.9.3 Any part which is normally purchased that is optionally shown as a Made part must have supporting documentation submitted to prove team manufacture.\n5.3.9.4 Teams costing Bought parts as Made parts will be penalized.\n\n### 5.3.10 Add Item Request\n\n5.3.10.1 An Add Item Request must be submitted on the FSAE Online Website to add items to the Cost Tables for individual team requirements.\n5.3.10.2 After review, the item may be added to the Cost Table with an appropriate cost. Support materials, such as technical drawings, will not be released.\n\n### 5.3.12 Cost Report Penalties Process\n\n5.3.12.1 The following procedure will be used in determining penalties:\na. Penalty A will be calculated using procedure Penalty Method A - Fixed Point Deductions\nb. Penalty B will be calculated using procedure Penalty Method B - Adjusted Cost Additions\nc. The higher of the two penalties will be applied against the Cost Event score\n\n- Penalty A expressed in points will be deducted from the Cost Event score\n- $\\quad$ Penalty B expressed in dollars will be added to the Adjusted Cost of the vehicle\n5.3.12.2 Any error that results in a team over reporting a cost in their Cost Report will not be further penalized.\n5.3.12.3 Any instance where a team's score benefits by an intentional or unintentional error on the part of the students will be corrected on a case by case basis.\n\n\n### 5.3.12.4 Penalty Method A - Fixed Point Deductions\n\na. From the Bill of Material, the Cost Judges will determine if all Parts and Processes have been included in the analysis.\nb. In the case of any omission or error a penalty proportional to the BOM level of the error will be imposed:\n\n- Missing/inaccurate Material, Process, Fastener 1 point\n- Missing/inaccurate Part 3 point\n- Missing/inaccurate Assembly 5 point\nc. Each of the penalties listed above supersedes the previous penalty.\n\nExample - if a point deduction is given for a missing Assembly, the missing Parts are ignored.", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=121, markdown='d. Differences other than those listed above will be deducted at the discretion of the Cost Judges.\nS.3.12.5 Penalty Method B - Adjusted Cost Additions\na. The table cost for the missing or incomplete items will be calculated from the standard Cost Tables.\nb. The penalty will be a value equal to twice the difference between the team cost and the correct cost for all items in error.\nPenalty $=2 \\times$ (Table Cost - Team Reported Cost)\nThe table costs of all items in error are included in the calculation. A missing Assembly would include the price of all Parts, Materials, Processes and Fasteners making up the Assembly.\n\n# 5.3.13 Event Day and Discussion \n\nS.3.13.1 The team must present their vehicle at the designated time\nS.3.13.2 The vehicle must have the tires and wheels declared as Dry Tires per V.4.3.1 installed during Cost Event judging\nS.3.13.3 Teams may be required to bring a copy of the Cost Report and Cost Addendum to Cost Judging\nS.3.13.4 The Cost Judges will:\na. Review whether the Cost Report accurately reflects the vehicle as presented\nb. Review the manufacturing feasibility of the vehicle\nc. This includes competition, inspection and practice areas.\nD.1.2.2 Staging Area - Any area(s) inside the Dynamic Area prior to the entry to an event for the purpose of gathering those vehicles that are about to start.\n\n## D. 2 PIT AND PADDOCK\n\n## D.2.1 Vehicle Movement\n\nD.2.1.1 Outside of the Dynamic Area(s), vehicles must be pushed at a normal walking pace using the Push Bar (VE.2.2), with a driver in the cockpit and with another team member walking beside\nD.2.1.2 The team may move the vehicle with\na. All four wheels on the ground\nb. The rear wheels supported on dollies, by push bar mounted wheels\n\nThe external wheels supporting the rear of the vehicle must be non pivoting so the vehicle travels only where the front wheels are steered. The driver must always be able to steer and brake the vehicle normally.\nD.2.1.3 When the Push Bar is attached, the engine must stay off, unless authorized by the officials\nD.2.1.4 Vehicles must be Shutdown when being moved around the paddock\nD.2.1.5 Vehicles with wings must have two team members, one walking on each side of the vehicle when the vehicle is being pushed\nD.2.1.6 A 25 point penalty may be assessed for each violation\n\n## D.2.2 Fueling and Charging\n\n(IC only) Officials must conduct all fueling activities in the designated location.\n(EV only) Accumulator charging must be done in the designated location EV.11.5\n\n## D.2.3 Powertrain Operation\n\nIn the paddock, (IC) Engines may be run or (EV) Tractive System may be Active if all three:\na. The drive wheels are minimum 10 cm off the ground, OR the drive wheels are removed', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=125, markdown='# D. 3 DRIVING \n\n## D.3.1 Drivers Meetings - Attendance Required\n\nAll drivers for an event must attend the drivers meeting(s). The driver for an event will be disqualified if he/she does not attend the driver meeting for the event.\n\n## D.3.2 Dynamic Area Limitations\n\nRefer to the Event Website for specific information\nD.3.2.1 The organizer may specify restrictions for the Dynamic Area. These could include limiting the number of team members and what may be brought into the area.\nD.3.2.3 The organizer may establish requirements for persons in the Dynamic Area, such as closed toe shoes or long pants.\n\n## D.3.3 Driving Under Power\n\nD.3.3.1 Vehicles must move under their own power only when inside the designated Dynamic Area(s), unless otherwise directed by the officials.\nD.3.3.2 Driving a vehicle outside of scheduled events or scheduled practice will result in a 200 point penalty for the first violation and disqualification for a second violation.\n\n## D.3.4 Driving Offsite - Prohibited\n\nTeams found to have driven their vehicle at an offsite location during the period of the competition will be excluded from the competition.\n\n## D.3.5 Driver Equipment\n\nD.3.5.1 All Driver Equipment and Harness must be worn by the driver anytime in the cockpit with:\na. A time penalty may be assessed.\nD.4.1.3 Black Flag with Orange Dot - Pull into the Driver Change Area for a mechanical inspection, something has been observed that needs closer inspection.\nD.4.1.4 Blue Flag - Pull into the designated passing zone to be passed by a faster competitor. Obey the corner workers signals at the end of the passing zone to merge into competition.\nD.4.1.5 Checkered Flag - Run has been completed. Exit the course at the designated point.\nD.4.1.6 Green Flag - Approval to begin your run, enter the course under direction of the starter. If you stall the vehicle, please restart and await another Green Flag\nD.4.1.7 Red Flag - Come to an immediate safe controlled stop on the course. Pull to the side of the course as much as possible to keep the course open. Follow corner worker directions.\nD.4.1.8 Yellow Flag (Stationary) - Danger, SLOW DOWN, be prepared to take evasive action, something has happened beyond the flag station. NO PASSING unless directed by the corner workers.\nD.4.1.9 Yellow Flag (Waved) - Great Danger, SLOW DOWN, evasive action is most likely required, BE PREPARED TO STOP, something has happened beyond the flag station, NO PASSING unless directed by the corner workers.\n\n## D.4.2 Informational Flags\n\nD.4.2.1 An Information Flag communicates to the driver, but requires no specific action.\nD.4.2.2 Red and Yellow Striped Flag - Something is on the racing surface that should not be there. Be prepared for evasive maneuvers to avoid the situation.\nD.4.2.3 White Flag - There is a slow moving vehicle on the course. Be prepared to approach it at a cautious rate.\n\n## D. 5 WEATHER CONDITIONS\n\n## D.5.1 Operating Adjustments\n\nD.5.1.1 The organizer may alter the conduct and scoring of the competition based on weather conditions.\nD.5.1.2 No adjustments will be made to times for running in differing Operating Conditions.\nD.5.1.3 The minimum performance levels to score points may be adjusted by the Officials.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=127, markdown="# D.5.2 Operating Conditions \n\nD.5.2.1 The following operating conditions will be recognized:\n\n- Dry\n- Damp\n- Wet\nD.5.2.2 The current operating condition will be decided by the Officials and may change at any time.\nD.5.2.3 The current operating condition will be prominently displayed at the Dynamic Area, and may be communicated by other means.\n\n\n## D. 6 TIRES AND TIRE CHANGES\n\n## D.6.1 Tire Requirements\n\nD.6.1.1 Teams must run the tires allowed for each Operating Condition:\n\n| Operating Condition | Tires Allowed |\n| :--: | :--: |\n| Dry | Dry ( V.4.3.1) |\n| Damp | Dry or Wet |\n| Wet | Wet ( V.4.3.2) |\n\nD.6.1.2 When the operating condition is Damp, teams may change between Dry Tires and Wet Tires:\na. Any time during the Acceleration, Skidpad, and Autocross Events\nb. Any time before starting their Endurance Event\n\n## D.6.2 Tire Changes during Endurance\n\nD.6.2.1 All tire changes after a vehicle has received the Green flag to start the Endurance Event must take place in the Driver Change Area.\nD.6.2.2 If the Operating Condition changes to Wet during Endurance, the track will be Red Flagged or vehicles will be Black Flagged and brought into the Driver Change Area\nD.6.2.3 The allowed tire changes and associated conditions are given in the following tables.\n\n| Existing <br> Operating <br> Condition | Currently <br> Running on: | Operating Condition Changed to: |  |  |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n|  |  | Dry | Damp | Wet |\n| Dry | Dry Tires | ok | A | B |\n| Damp | Dry Tires | ok | A | B |\n| Damp | Wet Tires | C | C | ok |\n| Wet | Wet Tires | C | C | ok |\n\n\n|  | Requirement | Allowed at <br> Driver Change? |\n| :--: | :-- | :--: |\n| A | may change from Dry to Wet | Yes |\n| B | MUST change from Dry to Wet | Yes |\n| C | may change from Wet to Dry | NO |\n\nD.6.2.4 Time allowed to change tires:\na. Change to Wet Tires - Any time in excess of 10 minutes without driver change, or 13 minutes with Driver Change, will be added to the team's total time for Endurance", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=128, markdown="b. Change to Dry Tires - The time used to change to Dry Tires will be added to the team's total time for Endurance\nD.6.2.5 If the vehicle has a tire puncture,\na. The wheel and tire may be replaced with an identical wheel and tire\nb. When the puncture is caused by track debris and not a result of component failure or the vehicle itself, the tire change time will not count towards the team's total time.\n\n# D. 7 DRIVER LIMITATIONS \n\n## D.7.1 Three Event Limit\n\nD.7.1.1 An individual team member may not drive in more than three events.\nD.7.1.2 The Efficiency Event is considered a separate event although it is conducted simultaneously with the Endurance Event.\n\nA minimum of four drivers are required to participate in all of the dynamic events.\n\n## D. 8 DEFINITIONS\n\nD.8.1.1 DOO - Cone is Down or Out when one or both:\na. Cone has been knocked over (Down)\nb. The entire base of the cone lies outside the box marked around the cone in its undisturbed position (Out)\nD.8.1.2 DNF - Did Not Finish - The team attempted a run, but did not complete it, or was not allowed to complete it\nD.8.1.3 DQ - Disqualified - run(s) or event(s) no longer valid\nD.8.1.4 Gate - The path between two cones through which the vehicle must pass. Two cones, one on each side of the course define a gate. Two sequential cones in a slalom define a gate.\nD.8.1.5 Entry Gate -The path marked by cones which establishes the required path the vehicle must take to enter the course.\nD.8.1.6 Exit Gate - The path marked by cones which establishes the required path the vehicle must take to exit the course.\nD.8.1.7 OC - Off Course\na. The vehicle did not pass through a gate in the required direction.\nb. The vehicle has all four wheels outside the course boundary as indicated by cones, edge marking or the edge of the paved surface.\n\nWhere more than one boundary indicator is used on the same course, the narrowest track will be used when determining Off Course penalties.\n\n## D. 9 ACCELERATION EVENT\n\nThe Acceleration event evaluates the vehicle acceleration in a straight line on flat pavement.\n\n## D.9.1 Acceleration Layout\n\nD.9.1.1 Course length will be 75 m from starting line to finish line\nD.9.1.2 Course width will be minimum 4.9 m wide as measured between the inner edges of the bases of the course edge cones\nD.9.1.3 Cones are placed along the course edges at intervals, approximately 6 m", images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=129, markdown='D.9.1.4 Cone locations are not marked on the pavement\n\n# D.9.2 Acceleration Procedure \n\nD.9.2.1 Each team may attempt up to four runs, using two drivers, limited to two runs for each driver\nD.9.2.2 Runs with the first driver have priority\nD.9.2.3 Each Acceleration run is performed as follows:\na. The foremost part of the vehicle will be staged at 0.30 m behind the starting line\nb. A Green Flag or light signal will give the approval to begin the run\nc. Timing starts when the vehicle crosses the starting line\nd. Timing ends when the vehicle crosses the finish line\nD.9.2.4 Each driver may go to the front of the staging line immediately after their first run to make a second run\n\n## D.9.3 Acceleration Penalties\n\nD.9.3.1 Cones (DOO)\n\nTwo second penalty for each DOO (including entry and exit gate cones) on that run\nD.9.3.2 Off Course (OC)\n\nDNF for that run\n\n## D.9.4 Acceleration Scoring\n\nD.9.4.1 Scoring Term Definitions:\n\n- Corrected Time = Acceleration Run Time + (DOO * 2 )\n- $\\quad$ Tyour - the best Corrected Time for the team\n- $\\quad$ Tmin - the lowest Corrected Time recorded for any team\n- Tmax - 150\\% of Tmin\nD.9.4.2 When Tyour < Tmax. the team score is calculated as:\n\nAcceleration Score $=\\quad 95.5 \\times \\frac{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tyour })-1}{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tmin })-1}+4.5$\nD.9.4.3 When Tyour > Tmax, Acceleration Score $=4.5$\n\n## D. 10 SKIDPAD EVENT\n\nThe Skidpad event measures the vehicle cornering ability on a flat surface while making a constant radius turn.\n\n## D.10.1 Skidpad Layout\n\nD.10.1.1 Course Design\n\n- Two pairs of concentric circles in a figure of eight pattern\n- Centers of the circles 18.25 m apart\n- Inner circles 15.25 m in diameter\n- Outer circles 21.25 m in diameter\n- Driving path the 3.0 m wide path between the inner and outer circles', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=130, markdown='# D.10.1.2 Cone Placement \n\na. Sixteen (16) pylons will be placed around the inside of each inner circle and thirteen (13) pylons will be positioned around the outside of each outer circle in the pattern shown in the Skidpad layout diagram.\nb. Each circle will be marked with a chalk line, inside the inner circle and outside the outer circle\n\nThe Skidpad layout diagram shows the circles for cone placement, not for course marking. Chalk lines are marked on the opposite side of the cones, outside the driving path\nc. Additional pylons will establish the entry and exit gates.\nd. A cone may be placed in the middle of the exit gate until the finish lap.\nD.10.1.3 Course Operation\na. Vehicles will enter and exit through gates on a 3.0 m wide path that is tangential to the circles where they meet.\nb. The line between the centers of the circles defines the start/stop line.\nc. A lap is defined as traveling around one of the circles from the start/stop line and returning to the start/stop line.\n![img-26.jpeg](img-26.jpeg)\n\n## D.10.2 Skidpad Procedure\n\nD.10.2.1 Each team may attempt up to four runs, using two drivers, limited to two runs for each driver.\nD.10.2.2 Runs with the first driver have priority\nD.10.2.3 Each Skidpad run is performed as follows:\na. A Green Flag or light signal will give the approval to begin the run\nb. The vehicle will enter perpendicular to the figure eight and will take one full lap on the right circle\nc. The next lap will be on the right circle and will be timed', images=[OCRImageObject(id='img-26.jpeg', top_left_x=309, top_left_y=919, bottom_right_x=1387, bottom_right_y=1647, image_base64='data:image/jpeg;base64,', image_annotation='{\n  "image_type": "diagram",\n  "short_description": "A diagram of a circular track layout for a race or event.",\n  "summary": "The image is a diagram showing a circular track layout used for a race or event. Immediately following the second lap, the vehicle will enter the left circle for the third lap\ne. The fourth lap will be on the left circle and will be timed\nf. Immediately upon finishing the fourth lap, the vehicle will exit the track. The exit is at the intersection moving in the same direction as entered\nD.10.2.4 Each driver may go to the front of the staging line immediately after their first run to make a second run\n\n# D.10.3 Skidpad Penalties \n\nD.10.3.1 Cones (DOO)\n\nA 0.125 second penalty for each DOO (including entry and exit gate cones) on that run\nD.10.3.2 Off Course (OC)\n\nDNF for that run. Vehicles that stall or spin out may continue if they have not gone Off Course.\nD.10.3.3 Incorrect Laps\n\nVehicles that run an incorrect number of laps or run the laps in the wrong sequence will be DNF for that run.\n\n## D.10.4 Skidpad Scoring\n\nD.10.4.1 Scoring Term Definitions\n\n- $\\quad$ Corrected Time $=($ Right Lap Time + Left Lap Time $) / 2+$ (DOO * 0.125 )\n- $\\quad$ Tyour - the best Corrected Time for the team\n- $\\quad$ Tmin - is the lowest Corrected Time recorded for any team\n- Tmax - $125 \\%$ of Tmin\nD.10.4.2 When Tyour < Tmax. the team score is calculated as:\n\n$$\n\\text { Skidpad Score }=\\quad 71.5 \\times \\frac{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tyour })^{2}-1}{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tmin })^{2}-1}+3.5\n$$\n\nD.10.4.3 When Tyour > Tmax, Skidpad Score $=3.5$\n\n## D. 11 AUTOCROSS EVENT\n\nThe Autocross event evaluates the vehicle maneuverability and handling qualities on a tight course\n\n## D.11.1 Autocross Layout\n\nD.11.1.1 The Autocross course will be designed with the following specifications. Average speeds should be $40 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$ to $48 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$\na. Straights: No longer than 60 m with hairpins at both ends\nb. Straights: No longer than 45 m with wide turns on the ends\nc. Constant Turns: 23 m to 45 m diameter\nd. Hairpin Turns: 9 m minimum outside diameter (of the turn)\ne. Slaloms: Cones in a straight line with 7.62 m to 12.19 m spacing\nf. Miscellaneous: Chicanes, multiple turns, decreasing radius turns, etc.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=132, markdown='g. Minimum track width: 3.5 m\nh. Length of each run should be approximately 0.80 km\nD.11.1.2 The Autocross course specifications may deviate from the above to accommodate event site requirements.\n\n# D.11.2 Autocross Procedure \n\nD.11.2.1 Each team may attempt up to four runs, using two drivers, limited to two runs for each driver\nD.11.2.2 Runs with the first driver have priority\nD.11.2.3 Each Autocross run is performed as follows:\na. The vehicle will be staged at a specific distance behind the starting line\nb. A Green Flag or light signal will give the approval to begin the run\nc. Timing starts when the vehicle crosses the starting line\nd. Timing ends when the vehicle crosses the finish line\nD.11.2.4 Each driver may go to the front of the staging line immediately after their first run to make a second run\n\n## D.11.3 Autocross Penalties\n\nD.11.3.1 Cones (DOO)\n\nTwo second penalty for each DOO (including cones after the finish line) on that run\nD.11.3.2 Off Course (OC)\na. When an OC occurs, the driver must reenter the track at or prior to the point of exit or receive a 20 second penalty\nb. Penalties will not be assessed for accident avoidance or other reasons deemed sufficient by the track officials.\nD.11.3.3 Missed Slalom\n\nMissing one or more gates of a given slalom will be counted as one Off Course\n\n## D.11.4 Autocross Scoring\n\nD.11.4.1 Scoring Term Definitions:\n\n- $\\quad$ Corrected Time $=$ Autocross Run Time $+(\\mathrm{DOO} * 2)+(\\mathrm{OC} * 20)$\n- $\\quad$ Tyour - the best Corrected Time for the team\n- $\\quad$ Tmin - the lowest Corrected Time recorded for any team\n- Tmax - 145\\% of Tmin\nD.11.4.2 When Tyour < Tmax. the team score is calculated as:\n\n$$\n\\text { Autocross Score }=\\quad 118.5 \\times \\frac{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tyour })-1}{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tmin })-1}+6.5\n$$\n\nD.11.4.3 When Tyour > Tmax, Autocross Score $=6.5$\n\n## D. 12 ENDURANCE EVENT\n\nThe Endurance event evaluates the overall performance of the vehicle and tests the durability and reliability.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=133, markdown='# D.12.1 Endurance General Information \n\nD.12.1.1 The organizer may establish one or more requirements to allow teams to compete in the Endurance event.\nD.12.1.2 Each team may attempt the Endurance event once.\nD.12.1.3 The Endurance event consists of two Endurance runs, each using a different driver, with a Driver Change between.\nD.12.1.4 Teams may not work on their vehicles once their Endurance event has started\nD.12.1.5 Multiple vehicles may be on the track at the same time\nD.12.1.6 Wheel to Wheel racing is prohibited.\nD.12.1.7 Vehicles must not be driven in reverse\n\n## D.12.2 Endurance Layout\n\nD.12.2.1 The Endurance event will consist of multiple laps over a closed course to a total distance of approximately 22 km .\nD.12.2.2 The Endurance course will be designed with the following specifications. Average speed should be $48 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$ to $57 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$ with top speeds of approximately $105 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}$.\na. Straights: No longer than 77 m with hairpins at both ends\nb. Straights: No longer than 61 m with wide turns on the ends\nc. Constant Turns: 30 m to 54 m diameter\nd. Hairpin Turns: 9 m minimum outside diameter (of the turn)\ne. Slaloms: Cones in a straight line with 9 m to 15 m spacing\nf. Miscellaneous: Chicanes, multiple turns, decreasing radius turns, etc.\ng. Minimum track width: 4.5 m\nh. Designated passing zones at several locations\nD.12.2.3 The Endurance course specifications may deviate from the above to accommodate event site requirements.\n\n## D.12.3 Endurance Run Order\n\nThe Endurance Run Order is established to let vehicles of similar speed potential be on track together to reduce the need for passing.\nD.12.3.1 The Endurance Run Order:\na. Should be primarily based on the Autocross event finish order\nb. Should include the teams eligible for Endurance which did not compete in the Autocross event.\nc. May be altered by the organizer to accommodate specific circumstances or event considerations\nD.12.3.2 Each team must keep track of the Endurance Run Order and have their vehicle fueled, in line and prepared to start when their turn to run arrives.\n\n## D.12.4 Endurance Vehicle Starting / Restarting\n\nD.12.4.1 Teams that are not ready to run or cannot start their Endurance event in the allowed time when their turn in the Run Order arrives:\na. Will receive a time penalty (D.12.12.5)', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=134, markdown='b. May then run at the discretion of the Officials\nD.12.4.2 Following Driver Change, the vehicle will be allowed up to 120 seconds (two minutes) to (IC) restart the engine or to (EV) enable the Tractive System.\na. The time will start when the driver first tries to restart the engine or to enable the Tractive System.\nb. The time to attempt start / restart is not counted towards the Endurance time\nD.12.4.3 If a vehicle stalls on the track, it will be allowed one lap by the vehicle that is following it (approximately 60 seconds) to restart. This time counts toward the Endurance time.\nD.12.4.4 If starts / restarts are not accomplished in the above times, the vehicle may be DNF.\n\n# D.12.5 Endurance Event Procedure \n\nD.12.5.1 Vehicles will be staged per the Endurance Run Order\nD.12.5.2 Endurance Event sequence:\na. The first driver will perform an Endurance Run per D.12.6 below\nb. The Driver Change must then be performed per D.12.8 below\nc. The second driver will perform an Endurance Run per D.12.6 below\nD.12.5.3 The Endurance Event is complete when both:\n\n- the team has completed the specified number of laps\n- the second driver crosses the finish line\n\n\n## D.12.6 Endurance Run Procedure\n\nD.12.6.1 A Green Flag or light signal will give the approval to begin the run\nD.12.6.2 The driver will drive approximately half of the Endurance distance\nD.12.6.3 A Checkered Flag will be displayed\nD.12.6.4 The vehicle must exit the track into the Driver Change Area\n\n## D.12.7 Driver Change Limitations\n\nD.12.7.1 The team may bring only the following into the Driver Change Area:\na. Three team members, including the driver or drivers\nb. (EV Only) The three team members must consist of an ESO EV.11.1.1 and two drivers.\nc. Minimal tools necessary to adjust the vehicle to fit the second driver and/or change tires Team members may only carry tools by hand (no carts, tool chests etc)\nd. Each extra person entering the Driver Change Area: 20 point penalty\nD.12.7.2 The only work permitted during Driver Change is:\na. Operation of Master Switches IC.9.3, EV.7.9, Main Switch IC.9.4, or Shutdown Buttons EV.7.10\nb. Adjustments to fit the driver IN.14.2.2\nc. Tire changes per D.6.2\n\n## D.12.8 Driver Change Procedure\n\nD.12.8.1 The Driver Change will be performed in this sequence:\na. Vehicle will stop in Driver Change Area', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=135, markdown='b. First Driver turns off the engine / Tractive System. Driver Change time starts.\nc. First Driver exits the vehicle\nd. Any necessary adjustments may be made to the vehicle to fit the Second Driver IN.14.2.2\ne. Second Driver is secured in the vehicle\nf. Second Driver is ready to start the engine / enable the Tractive System. Driver Change time stops.\ng. Second Driver receives permission to continue\nh. The vehicle engine is started or Tractive System enabled. See D.12.4\ni. The vehicle stages to go back onto course, at the direction of the event officials\nD.12.8.2 Three minutes are allowed for the team to complete the Driver Change\na. Any additional time for inspection of the vehicle and the Driver Equipment is not included in the Driver Change time\nb. Time in excess of the allowed will be added to the team Endurance time\nD.12.8.3 The Driver Change Area will be placed where the timing system will see the Driver Change as a long lap which will be deleted from the total time.\n\n# D.12.9 Breakdowns \\& Stalls \n\nD.12.9.1 If a vehicle breaks down or cannot restart, it will be removed from the course by track workers and scored DNF\nD.12.9.2 If a vehicle stalls, or ingests a cone, etc., it may be allowed to continue, subject to D.12.1.4 and D.12.4\n\n## D.12.10 Endurance Event - Black Flags\n\nD.12.10.1 A Black Flag will be shown at the designated location\nD.12.10.2 The vehicle must pull into the Driver Change Area at the first opportunity\nD.12.10.3 The amount of time spent in the Driver Change Area is at the discretion of the officials.\nD.12.10.4 Driving Black Flag\na. May be shown for any reason such as aggressive driving, failing to obey signals, not yielding for passing, not driving inside the designated course, etc.\nb. Course officials will discuss the situation with the driver\nc. The time spent in Black Flag or a time penalty may be included in the Endurance Run time.\nd. If not possible to impose a penalty by a stop under a Black Flag, (not enough laps left), or during post event review, officials may impose a penalty D.14.2\nD.12.10.5 Mechanical Black Flag\na. May be shown for any reason to question the vehicle condition\nb. Time spent off track is not included in the Endurance Run time.\nD.12.10.6 Based on the inspection or discussion during a Black Flag period, the vehicle may not be allowed to continue the Endurance Run and will be scored DNF\n\n## D.12.11 Endurance Event - Passing\n\nD.12.11.1 Passing during Endurance may only be done in the designated passing zones, under the control of the track officials.', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=136, markdown='D.12.11.2 Passing zones have two parallel lanes - a slow lane for the vehicles that are being passed and a fast lane for vehicles that are making a pass.\nD.12.11.3 When a pass is to be made:\na. A slower leading vehicle will receive a Blue Flag\nb. The slower vehicle must move into the slow lane and decelerate.\nc. The following faster vehicle will continue in the fast lane and make the pass.\nd. The vehicle that had been passed may reenter traffic only under the control of the passing zone exit flag.\nD.12.11.4 Passing rules do not apply to vehicles that are passing disabled vehicles on the course or vehicles that have spun out and are not moving. When passing a disabled or off track vehicle, slow down, drive cautiously and be aware of all the vehicles and track workers in the area.\n\n# D.12.12 Endurance Penalties \n\nD.12.12.1 Cones (DOO)\n\nTwo second penalty for each DOO (including cones after the finish line) on that run\nD.12.12.2 Off Course (OC)\na. When an OC occurs, the driver must reenter the track at or prior to the point of exit or receive a 20 second penalty\nb. Penalties will not be assessed for accident avoidance or other reasons deemed sufficient by the track officials.\nD.12.12.3 Missed Slalom\n\nMissing one or more gates of a given slalom will be counted as one Off Course\nD.12.12.4 Penalties for Moving or Post Event Violations\na. Black Flag penalties per D.12.10, if applicable\nb. Post Event Inspection penalties per D.14.2, if applicable\nD.12.12.5 Endurance Starting (D.12.4.1)\n\nTwo minutes ( 120 seconds) penalty\nD.12.12.6 Vehicle Operation\n\nThe Chief Marshall/Director of Operations may end the Endurance event (DNF) a vehicle if, for any reason including driver inexperience or mechanical problems, it is too slow or being driven in a manner that demonstrates an inability to properly control.\n\n## D.12.13 Endurance Scoring\n\nD.12.13.1 Scoring Term Definitions:\n\n- Endurance Run Time - Total Time for both Drivers, minus the Driver Change lap, minus any Mechanical Black Flag Time, plus any Penalty time D.14.2\n- $\\quad$ Corrected Time $=$ Endurance Run Time $+(\\mathrm{DOO} * 2)+(\\mathrm{OC} * 20)$\n- $\\quad$ Tyour - the Corrected Time for the team\n- Tmin - the lowest Corrected Time recorded for any team\n- Tmax - 145\\% of Tmin', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=137, markdown='D.12.13.2 The vehicle must complete the Endurance Event to receive a score based on their Corrected Time\na. If Tyour < Tmax, the team score is calculated as:\n\n$$\n\\text { Endurance Time Score }=\\quad 250 \\times \\frac{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tyour })-1}{(\\text { Tmax } / \\text { Tmin })-1}\n$$\n\nb. If Tyour > Tmax, Endurance Time Score $=0$\nD.12.13.3 The vehicle receives points based on the laps and/or parts of Endurance completed.\n\nThe Endurance Laps Score is worth up to 25 points\nD.12.13.4 The Endurance Score is calculated as:\n\nEndurance Score $=$ Endurance Time Score + Endurance Laps Score\n\n# D. 13 EFFICIENCY EVENT \n\nThe Efficiency event evaluates the fuel/energy used to complete the Endurance event\n\n## D.13.1 Efficiency General Information\n\nD.13.1.1 The Efficiency is based on a metric of the amount of fuel consumed or energy used and the lap time on the endurance course, averaged over the length of the event.\nD.13.1.2 The Efficiency score is based only on the distance the vehicle runs on the course during the Endurance event, and the total fuel/energy used. No adjustment to distance or fuel/energy will be made.\n\n## D.13.2 Efficiency Procedure\n\nD.13.2.1 For IC vehicles:\na. The fuel tank must be filled to the fuel level line (IC.5.4.5)\nb. During fuelling, once filled to the scribe line, no shaking or tilting of the tank, fuel system, or the entire vehicle is allowed.\nD.13.2.2 (EV only) The vehicle may be fully charged\nD.13.2.3 The vehicle will then compete in the Endurance event, refer to D.12.5\nD.13.2.4 Vehicles must power down after leaving the course and be pushed to the fueling station or data download area\nD.13.2.5 For Internal Combustion vehicles (IC):\na. The Fuel Tank must be filled to the Fuel Level Line (IC.5.4.5) to measure fuel used. IC.5.5.1\nb. If the fuel level changes after refuelling:\n\n- Additional fuel will be added to return the fuel tank level to the fuel level line.\n- Twice this amount will be added to the previously measured fuel consumption\nc. If damage or a potential environmental hazard (example - Fuel Tank leakage) exists, the Fuel Tank will not be refilled D.13.3.4\nD.13.2.6 For Electric Vehicles (EV):\na. Energy Meter data must be downloaded to measure energy used and check for Violations EV.3.3\nb. Penalties will be applied per EV.3.5 and/or D.13.3.4', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=138, markdown='# D.13.3 Efficiency Eligibility \n\nD.13.3.1 Maximum Time\n\nVehicles whose average Endurance laptime exceeds 1.45 times the average Endurance laptime of the fastest team that completes the Endurance event will receive zero points\nD.13.3.2 Maximum Fuel/Energy Used\n\nVehicles whose corrected average (IC) fuel consumption / (EV) energy equivalent per lap exceeds the values in D.13.4.5 will receive zero points\nD.13.3.3 Partial Completion of Endurance\na. Vehicles which cross the start line following Driver Change are eligible for Efficiency points\nb. Other vehicles will receive zero points\nD.13.3.4 Cannot Measure Fuel/Energy Used\n\nThe vehicle will receive zero points\n\n## D.13.4 Efficiency Scoring\n\nD.13.4.1 Conversion Factors\n\nEach fuel or energy used is converted using the factors:\na. Gasoline / Petrol\n2.31 kg of $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ per liter\nb. E85\n1.65 kg of $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ per liter\nc. Electric\n0.65 kg of $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ per kWh\nD.13.4.2 (EV only) Full credit is given for energy recovered through regenerative braking\nD.13.4.3 Scoring Term Definitions:\n\n- $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ min - the smallest mass of $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ used by any competitor who is eligible for Efficiency\n- $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ your - the mass of $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ used by the team being scored\n- Tmin - the lowest Endurance time of the fastest team which is eligible for Efficiency\n- Tyour - same as Endurance (D.12.13.1)\n- Lapyours - the number of laps driven by the team being scored\n- Laptotal Tmin and Latptotal $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ min - be the number of laps completed by the teams which set Tmin and $\\mathrm{CO}_{2} \\mathrm{~min}$, respectively\nD.13.4.4 The Efficiency Factor is calculated by:\n\n$$\n\\text { Efficiency Factor }=\\frac{\\text { Tmin } / \\text { LapTotal }_{\\text {Tmin }}}{\\text { Tyours / Lap yours }} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{CO}_{2} \\text { min / LapTotal } \\mathrm{CO}_{2} \\text { min }}{\\mathrm{CO}_{2} \\text { your / Lap yours }}\n$$\n\nD.13.4.5 EfficiencyFactor min is calculated using the above formula with:\n\n- $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ your\n(IC) equivalent to $60.06 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{CO}_{2} / 100 \\mathrm{~km}$ (based on gasoline $26 \\mathrm{ltr} / 100 \\mathrm{~km}$ )\n- $\\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ your\n(EV) equivalent to $20.02 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{CO}_{2} / 100 \\mathrm{~km}$\n- Tyour\n1.45 times Tmin', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700)), OCRPageObject(index=139, markdown='D.13.4.6 When the team is eligible for Efficiency. the team score is calculated as:\n\n$$\n\\text { Efficiency Score }=\\quad 100 \\times \\frac{\\text { Efficiency Factor your - Efficiency Factor min }}{\\text { Efficiency Factor max - Efficiency Factor min }}\n$$\n\n# D. 14 POST ENDURANCE \n\n## D.14.1 Technical Inspection Required\n\nD.14.1.1 After Endurance and refuelling are completed, all vehicles must report to Technical Inspection.\nD.14.1.2 Vehicles may then be subject to IN. 15 Reinspection\n\n## D.14.2 Post Endurance Penalties\n\nD.14.2.1 Penalties may be applied to the Endurance and/or Efficiency events based on:\na. Infractions or issues during the Endurance Event (including D.12.10.4.d)\nb. Post Endurance Technical Inspection\nc. (EV only) Energy Meter violations EV.3.3, EV.3.5.2\nD.14.2.2 Any imposed penalty will be at the discretion of the officials.\n\n## D.14.3 Post Endurance Penalty Guidelines\n\nD.14.3.1 One or more minor violations (rules compliance, but no advantage to team): 15-30 sec\nD.14.3.2 Violation which is a potential or actual performance advantage to team: 120-360 sec\nD.14.3.3 Violation with potential or actual effect on safety or environment: 240 sec up to DNF or DQ\nD.14.3.4 Team may be DNF or DQ for:\na. Multiple violations involving safety, environment, or performance advantage\nb. A single substantial violation', images=[], dimensions=OCRPageDimensions(dpi=200, height=2200, width=1700))] model='mistral-ocr-2505-completion' usage_info=OCRUsageInfo(pages_processed=140, doc_size_bytes=1660545) document_annotation=None
